animal.description:
Cindy wants one thing this New Year- and thats a home to call her very own! Cindy has been waiting for her forever home for over 6 months- she is a special girl and is looking for just the right home where she can be the best dog she can be! Cindy is a sweet cuddle-muffin who loves her people. She is the type of dog that will cuddle on the couch and keep you warm, but also doesn't mind a good walk- as long as she is with her person Cindy is the happiest girl on earth! Cindy would prefer a home without other animals since she really doesn't want any animal friends. But that's okay because Cindy has a lot of love to give, and she just knows if you came to meet her, you would fall head-over-heels for her- just like she would for you! 

Cindy is a part of our Friends with Benefits Program, so not only does she have a waived adoption fee, she also will receive a special benefit package created just for her to help her and her new family. Cindy's benefits are free vaccinations and training sessions at our Rescue Ranch, medical care related to orthopedic issues at cost for life at our Rescue Ranch and one week of free boarding.

animal.description:
Jacque
Breed: Hound/Shepherd
Gender: Male
DOB: 1/29/18
Adoption Fee: $175
Jacque is a big boy with lots of love to give. He would love to greet you every day when you come home from work or school. Jacque will be a good fit for most homes. He's friendly, good with children and most dogs, he doesn't bark a lot and is doing very well on his house training. If you would like to make Jacque your new best friend please fill out an adoption application today!!!Please read the animal bios completely before requesting additional information as we do our best to answer the most frequently ask questions in these bios. 

In order to adopt one of our animals an application must be submitted and approved. You can find these applications by going to http://humanemorgan.org/index.php?page=adoption 

ABOUT ADOPTING FROM THE HSMC: 
The shelter address is 1170 Fairground Rd. Madison, GA 30650. For more information on any of our pets, please feel free to email us at INFO@HUMANEMORGAN.ORG give us a call at 706-343-9977. 
All dogs are heartworm negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
All cats are FeLv/FIV negative, current on vaccines/dewormings, and microchipped. 
We are open 10am-5pm Monday-Saturday, we schedule our last adoption at 4pm everyday to allow our staff enough time to feed and walk dogs. 
We are an animal shelter and therefore are not able to individually potty train our residents. Many adult dogs do arrive ""house broken"" however due to animal behavior any change in environment will make an emotional impact on the animals and therefore initiate unwanted behaviors during the acclamation period. Please keep this in mind. Puppies do not have the biological maturity to maintain absolute bladder or bowel control and will require a certain degree of potty training and house breaking. Please consider the time and commitment it takes to provide the necessary building blocks for these special babies, prior to submitting your application. 
If you have any questions please email us at info@humanemorgan.org and provide name of the animal you are interested in, in the subject line. 
Thank you, HSMC Staff 

ADOPTION FEES Adoption Fees may change without notice. Always verify the fee when finalizing the adoption. 
~ Cats and Kittens ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $100 
* 1-5 Years = $75 
* Over 5 Years = $50 
** Purebred cats and kittens may be subject to special pricing 

~ Mix Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $200 
* 1 -3 Years = $175 
* 4-8 Years = $150 
* Over 8 Years = $100

~ Purebred and Designer Breed Dogs ~ 
* Under 1 Year = $375 
* 1-3 Years = $350 
* 4-8 Years = $275 
* Over 8 Years = $150 

~ Medical and Special Needs ~ 
We have rescued dogs and cats which require additional medical care or that have special needs which are not life threatening. In these cases we may require a higher fee to help recoup the costs of their care while at our rescue.

animal.description:
Flopsy
Female
Age: 10 years old
Weight: 11lbs
Breed: Yorkie

Hi there! My name is Flopsy and I am the sweetest, kindest, and most quiet little lady on this side of the Mississippi! I never make a peep and love everyone I meet! I personally love it when I am in my persons arms being held while getting all the snuggles!
My previous chapter in life resulted in me not receiving regular vet care which is why I no longer have any teeth causing my tongue to flop out, hence my name. Since leaving my past behind and joining the rescued life, I have learned what true love and compassion really means. My foster mom has helped me make huge progress from helping me become a social butterfly, as well as teaching me how to walk well on a leash! I have also learned commands like sit and lay down. I am crate trained, but since I lived in a cage previously, I prefer a gated area if I am ever left alone. Unfortunately, I am not house trained. Due to my previous life, I have developed a severe case of incontinence and will require a family who not only is home most of the day allowing me to have frequent breaks to use the restroom outside, but also understands I will likely have accidents and is willing to love me no matter what! 

I do well with other dogs, cats and older children.

I am currently on medical hold while my foster mom and I figure out the best way to help with my need of frequent restroom breaks, but once we get a good plan in place, I will be ready to find my forever family!

If you are interested in meeting the sweet and cuddly Flopsy, apply to adopt at www.causeforcanines.org Adoption fee: $195
Children must be 12 years old or older
Must be an Ohio resident 25 years old or older

animal.description:
Hey I'm Kendra!

I am a 40 pound German Shepherd and Labrador Retriever mix. I am a super sweet doggy but I'm a little shy. With that said though, I love people and other dogs! I'm even good with kids and cats! I actually would do best in a home with an established dog because they can really show me the ropes. I deserve a happy home since I started off in a hoarding situation during the first part of my life where I was neglected and not taken care of. Please show me what it is like to live in a happy, quiet, healthy home! I am learning so many new and wonderful things from my foster home right now!

In order to meet me, you must make an appointment by emailing training@animalrescueneworleans.org.

My adoption fee is $200. This includes a spay/neuter, up-to-date vaccines, deworming, a microchip, a heartworm test, and, if needed, heartworm treatment.

________________________________________________

For all animals that have not been spayed or neutered a $100 deposit will be required in addition to the adoption fee. The deposit is refundable upon completion of the spay / neuter surgery.

For more information email: adopt@animalrescueneworleans.org.

To complete an application, please visit: https://animalrescueneworleans.org/adoptfoster/.

Please visit our facebook for more information about adoption specials, and adoption events. Events are a great way to meet multiple animals at a time!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Itty Bitty was a confiscation case in West Texas who was put into a high kill shelter. She was in a home with a drug addict and was fed Meth. Itty went through stomach pumping and medicinal and physical therapy to overcome what she went through.

Itty Bitty has been with both male and female dogs , she can be bossy and I'm sure wouldn't like all dogs. With proper slow introductions and with a non reactive playmate, she would likely do well. She chases cats. She's very people friendly but gets nervous during changes. Proper decompression time is a must.
She's house and crate trained, good with the foster's kids. She don't like being left outside long periods unless you are with her. She rides great in a car, and will play in baby pools with supervision

We would love to bring her here in mid January if she has a place to go. Need a dedicated foster or adopter to do so! Priority does go to applicant that can bring her to at least one vet visit in Golden Valley, Minnesota. Please apply on our website mattysheartandsoulanimalrescue.rescuegroups.org.

animal.description:
Sugar is ready for her new life! She just arrived at our shelter before Christmas. The first few chapters of Sugar's story is sad but we are sure the second half  - all the way to the finale will be a happy one! Sugar was born deaf or possibly mostly deaf (we are checking). And sadly her owner mistreated her. Extended family came in and rescued her and Sugar showed her gratitude with big pup kisses and a wagging tail. An amazing rescue group took her in and before she knew it -Sugar was on a plane to Washington! She just arrived here ready to start her new life! Those ears of hers might not catch every sound. But along with her sparkling eyes and white coat make her look like she might be part Bunny! 

Sugar will need a special home with a dog experienced family. A family with experience with training deaf dogs would be the best or maybe some sign language experience? Sugar has a lifetime of love to give to her forever family! Her DOB is 6/8/17 and she weighs 40 lbs.

Sugar's adoption fee is $259. This includes the Spay surgery, age appropriate current vaccines , microchip, and preventative flea treatment. .

For any questions regarding the application process visit our website https://www.sunnyskysshelter.org/our-adoption-process . If you have other questions you can email info@sunnyskysshelter.org .If you have not received a reply in 48 hours please verify your email address. Emailed questions are typically answered within 24 hours.

Thank you for your interest in one of our rescue pets. During this unprecedented time we venture into the unknown together and we thank you for your understanding and patience during this process. Together we are working toward the same goal of providing forever homes for all our furry friends.

Male - 4 years - 72 lbs - Microchipped - Neutered - ILHi! My name is Luca and I am a 4-year-old, 72 lb neutered male. I am already housebroken and crate-trained. I will need to be crated when left home alone and would prefer a home where someone is home more often than not.
I am a social boy who is good with all people: men, women, & young children. I will seek affection and enjoy being loved on. I will happily welcome visitors into our home!
*I enjoy playing with other dogs although I can get very rough in my wrestling style and insist on playing, so I would do best by myself or with a large, playful female. I will easily jump a fence if I see a dog outside of my yard, so I will require a 6-foot privacy fence at my home. I cannot go to a home with cats.
I walk fairly well on the leash, ride well in the car, and am high energy so I would love to be a companion for adventures! I like to play with my toys too.
I'm a happy boy looking for my perfect forever home with an active family. Could that be with you?
Follow me on Facebook: #EchoDogLuca
For more information, please contact adoptions@echodogs.org.

Echo Dogs fosters dogs in many states. Visit www.echodogs.org/available-dogs to see more of our dogs. Transportation for the adopted dog IS available. Remember, we are an all-volunteer foster rescue organization - we DO NOT have a physical shelter to visit. Our minimum adoption donation is $300. All dogs are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations and micro-chipped. Puppies under 6 months old may not be spayed/neutered. This would be the responsibility of the adopter at their own expense. Proof of spay/neuter will be required!
To review our adoption procedure and submit an online application, visit: www.echodogs.org/procedure

animal.description:
MEET MONTY!!

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in it's possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4381702.

Monty is a aging gentleman looking for his forever home. He loves attention from people. He knows sit and how to take treats gently. Despite his age he's an active boy who loves long walks, running and would be a great addition to an active home. He's still got a lot of pep in his step. Monty has been able to be friends with calm and easy going dogs at the shelter, but has shown some reactiveness to rowdy and rough dogs. If you have another pup at home, please bring him to the shelter for a meet and greet. Monty loves walks and does pull a bit on the leash according to volunteers, so he will need some help learning good leash manners. He does like treats, so that will help with any training endeavors.

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

animal.description:
Hank II
2.5 Years Old
House trained
No small dogs
No cats
Older children okay
Knows basic commands
Fostered in Newberg, OR

Swipe right for ME! Single male with diverse coloring (Brown/black/white Boxer) seeking a forever relationship! My name is Hank, and I like long walks on the beach (or just around the neighborhood), rides in the car, home cooked candlelight dinners by the fire, and snuggling up to watch a movie with you! Here's some fun facts about me - I love to dance, I'm a strong supporter of the 5 second rule, I think kale is overrated, and I'm probably on Santa's naughty list. Sometimes I put on my devil horns instead of my halo. But most of the time it's the halo.

You don't have to worry about me chewing up your shoes, peeing in the house, pooping in your shoes or any of those puppy things as I have definitely outgrown those young puppy urges. I'm currently in a foster home sleeping on a nice bed, having nutritious meals & treats, and getting lots of love. Don't get me wrong, I love this lady taking care of me, but I'm really hopeful that there is someone looking for their own dog, a forever friend so to speak!

If you are willing to make me a member of your family I promise to in return to shower you with lots of Boxer love. I will be your best friend and constant companion! I'll be honest I want to be in a family type of relationship, but I need slow introductions. My ideal family would have another large dog for me to play with that is not an alpha. I really don't like cats, so they and small dogs are a no-no for me. When it comes to humans though I like both men and women but, need slow introductions. As I mentioned I'm one to favor nice relaxing walks, a day of nosing around the yard or basking in the sun, but I may surprise you now and then with some zoomies around the yard just to keep life interesting! I'm starting to show my love of toys, but usually wait for my foster brother to entice me. I also like chewing on a good big bone.

I really am enjoying the good life that my foster mom is giving me. I have heard her say I have the most beautiful, soulful eyes. It's always nice to hear a compliment now and then right? I will admit that I'm rather scared while I'm on my leash walking and I react to people and dogs. My foster mom says a reactive dog class would be highly recommended. I really do love those who love me back. Don't worry if I follow you around while you do your thing - it's just me making sure that you know I'm around if you need me.

I would love to be your Boxer, your friend and forever companion. I would do best in a house with older children, no small dogs or cats and with a strong leader who is willing to be positive in reinforcing my learning. Do I sound like the boy for you? Apply today!

http://Bit.ly/WHBRadopt

www.Wigglinhomeboxerrescue.org
Email: wigglinhomeboxerrescue@gmail.com
Phone (360) 723-0219 2/2/21 5:21 PM

animal.description:
Michelle is going to make an exceptional dog for her furever family! About 1-3 years old and 42 lbs, this hound girl is as sweet and gentle as they come. She does well with kids and would be a great addition to a young family. She is reserved when meeting new people and in new situations, but quickly warms up and will begin asking for pets. Grab a spot next to her on the couch and snuggle up for cuddle time. She responds well to praise, and of course, treats. She is always happy and eager to make new dog friends and would be great in a multi-pet home, as she also gets along with cats. If her furry housemates don't want to play, she'll happily entertain herself with toys. Michelle walks well on the leash and would be content with an easy walk around the block each day or to go on longer hikes in the woods. She does have a strong hound nose and when she picks up a scent, she's inclined to follow it!
Michelle enjoys practicing her
doggy yoga and then
either retreat to her crate for a nap or curl up into a ball on the couch. Michelle happily takes her meals in her crate and will head there when she knows it's mealtime. She also rides well in the car.
Will you be the lucky household to love her and receive all the love she has to give in return?!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.

animal.description:
Lovely Lady is on her way to becoming a breast cancer survivor! 
•
8 year old Lady #A5396272 arrived from our Lancaster Animal Care Center with mammary tumors (as a result of not being spayed) on both sides and severe arthritis in her hips. She’s also on an anti-inflammatory for arthritis which she will need lifelong. Dr. Julia reported she was perfect while at the Vet...good girl Lady!
.
Healthcare for Homeless Animals provided funding for her #ForeverYoungSeniorWellnessExam at Malibu Coast Animal Hospital, where it was confirmed that she had mammary masses, and this is likely due to never being spayed ?. Most recently Lady had surgery to remove one mammary chain & she was finally spayed.
.
Here's some great news: her mammary masses were benign!! ? Next,  Lady will return to see Dr.Julia and have her other mammary chain removed along with dental work. ?  
.
Pretty Lady is a sweet girl & soon to be breast cancer survivor, who rides fantastic in a car,  and adores being with her volunteer friends. Lady is available for meet & greets to find her forever and ever home! ?  She is a sweet sheppie who is looking for a family with older children (MS age & up), a calm dog companion is ok. 
.
Please email agoura@animalcare.lacounty.gov to meet Lady!

agoura@animalcare.lacounty.gov 
(Please include your contact number)

animal.description: Hi there, I'm Hamm. As my name suggests, I am quite the little ham. I have LOTS of energy, and I love to run and play. I think toys are awesome and would love a person who can throw a ball or a stick for me - I really like sticks. I need some work on my manners, like not jumping and play biting. I've been doing much better about not play biting, and if you have a bone or a toy nearby I will quickly redirect my attention. I have a lot of pep in my step, so a person who can give me lots of exercise and is patient enough to work with me on training would be the best for me. I am a very smart boy, and my foster dad says I learned how to do "sit" and "paw" very quickly. I have also not had any accidents in his house, so I appear to be mostly or completely housebroken. I can get curious when left alone and might chew up some stuff I find, so crating me when you're away is a must for now. I do cry a little bit in my crate, but after a while I tucker myself out and fall asleep. I likely have too much energy for cats or very small children, though I do think kids are great fun. If you want a playful, spunky boy with lots of love to give, I would love to come home and play with you.

PUDDING is a delightful, 8-year-old, 35-pound Yellow Labrador Retriever mix.

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

To apply: 1. You must reside within our adoptable states: NY, NJ, CT, RI, MA, VT, NH, PA, DE, MD, VA 2. AND you MUST submit our online application, please CLICK HERE or copy & paste this link: http://www.nyabandonedangels.com/adopt-or-foster-application

Calling all Beagle lovers...

Happy #Tongue out Tuesday with Rocky Road! This very friendly and affectionate 9 month old Beagle is available for adoption at AACSR. Rocky was living in a shed since he was three months old. He was being trained for hunting. Rocky was an unhappy pup, he was not interested in hunting and could be heard whining and howling day and night for his freedom. His owner decided to surrender him to rescue.

Rocky will need time, patience and positive reinforcement training to get acclimated to a home environment. We think he will be a quick study! He is good with other dogs. animal.description:
Meet Loretta!

Cattle dogs are typically described as feisty, active dogs. While that may be true, my foster mom says I'm the perfect balance. I can walk a few miles on a leash, I can play chase with my resident dog for quite a while, or I can hang out at home and chew bones and tear up cardboard boxes (thank you Amazon). I am about 9 months old and currently weigh 27lbs. If I don't say so myself, I have the cutest set of ears you have ever seen! 

I currently live with one large dog and five pretty calm children. I love my foster mom too, but I don't need to follow her around all day because I'm pretty independent. As long as my crate is in your bedroom, I'll sleep in it quietly through most the night. I don't like my crate during the day, so my foster mom allows me to stay in the kitchen but has a pee pad by the door...... Just in case. I'm mostly potty trained but if you miss my cue, I might pee by the door! 

I'm also pretty smart! I already know the commands: sit, stay, and down. I am very food/treat motivated and I'll work hard for it. If my forever home has another dog, it should be a dog who can keep me in line while I'm learning the boundaries of play. Since I don't love my crate during the day, it would be great if someone was home to take care of me. 

Even though I'm a bit older, you have to remember I'm just a puppy and I'm still learning all the rules. I'm cautious and curious about new people/dogs so I'll bark at them until I know they are "ok" My shelter name is Loretta but my favorite nickname is Rosie!

Our standard adoption fee is $375 cash or check and $385 credit card ($10 processing fee).   It includes spay/neuter when age appropriate at our participating vets, age appropriate core vaccinations, fecal testing, deworming, flea and tick preventative,1st vet visit at one of our participating vets, and micro-chipping.

We must have an application, conduct a phone interview, and meet your entire family to approve an adoption. Please email adopt@safehavendogsIL.org for an application or additional details.

Please note that the breeds and sizes posted in this biography are educated best guesses and are not guaranteed.

DOG'S DESCRIPTION

Ricky is handsome boy who loves kids and is searching for a loving forever home where he can run, play and be your best buddy. Unfortunately, Ricky is heartworm positive and will need treatment. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.

Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.

Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org

Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!

animal.description:
MEET ETHEL!

This super special, super cute little lady is named Ethel! Ethel is an ~11 year old Poodle/Yorkie mix (our best guess) was rescued by Pennsylvania's Humane Law Enforcement during a neglect case. She spent a whole year in the shelter until her court case was resolved in Spring, 2020!

Needless to say, Ethel had a lot of making up to do and she has! When she entered the shelter it was discovered that she was diabetic and started insulin. Ethel formed cataracts due to the diabetes which resulted in blindness. Once we knew that her diabetes was regulated, we discovered that she was a candidate for cataract-removal surgery! She had surgery with an opthamologist this winter and while was already a happy, sweet girl, getting her sight back has transformed her back into a puppy! 

Ethel is happily living in foster care with other dogs and has met both large and small dogs while with the rescue. The kitties she lives with take the opportunity to snuggle with her whenever possible and Ethel doesn't mind one bit! One silly thing about Ethel is that she LOVES to hop into planters, baskets, anywhere she can curl up into a ball! Her favorite thing to do though, is snuggle up with her human friends! She'll happily hop into your lap or cuddle up next to you on the couch. Now that she has her sight back, Ethel really enjoys bouncing around and playing with the other pups and toys. She's an easy-going girl with mild manners and the sweetest disposition.

Ethel receives 2 units of insulin twice a day (with breakfast and dinner). She's a good girl who has no issues receiving her injections. While her diabetic needs have not changed during her time with City of Elderly Love, it's not uncommon for diabetic pets to need their insulin amounts tweaked over time. It's important that she receives her regular veterinary checkups. She's also completely housebroken! This sweetie will be an easy addition to most families!

Ethel is available for adoption through City of Elderly Love. She is spayed, vaccinated and microchipped. She has also received a dental cleaning and is heart worm negative. Interested in adopting her? Visit www.cityofelderlylove.org to complete an adoption questionnaire or email is at info@cityofelderlylove.org!

Dog's Name: Texas

Currently Living at: Boarding
Adoption Fee: $300
DOG'S DESCRIPTION
Texas is a sweet guy who is looking for a loving forever home where he can run, play and be your best buddy. Please consider opening your heart and home to this happy fellow. Texas gets along great with people but does not realize how big and strong he is, so he would be best suited in a home with older children. Texas does know a several commands. While Texas is dog friendly, he does have a dominant personality and would do best as an only dog. Texas is very active and needs a home with a fenced yard and a family that can provide him with lots of exercise. Texas is too active for apartment life.
Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.
Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.
Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org

Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Natalia is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet her.

Natalia is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~1 year
Weight: ~53lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Working on it! Takes some time to settle, but overall doing well with her cratetraining
Dog sociability: Selective with her dog friends. May be a match for some, but not all. She doesn't do well meeting dogs while on leash, but has done well with the dog in her foster home.
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Unknown
Ideal home: Natalia is an active adolescent dog looking for an active adopter! She will need daily mental and physical exercise. She is frustrated/reactive to other dogs on walks and would prefer a quieter neighborhood where she can work on her leash skills. 

Natalia is a wiggly teenager looking for a fun and energetic home! She loves to play and cuddle, but crates very well when its time to settle down. She's big and strong, but likes to think she's a lap dog, so be prepared for her to give you a lot of attention! Natalia is house-broken and hasn't had any accidents in her foster home. Seeing other dogs on walks is quite overstimulating for this gal, so she's hoping to find a home that can work on some good leash manners. She has done great with the other dog inside her foster home and playing in the yard. Natalia is a spunky sweetheart that will steal your heart in a matter of seconds!

Natalia's adoption fee is 300. She will be spayed on a future date (2/22/21) and a 50 refundable spay deposit will be required. She is up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative. She will require booster vaccines at the adopter's expense. 

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
No, it’s not the 1920’s, but yes my name is Whitey! I’m a fun-loving snow-white boxer at the perfect age of 8. Most likely 8, maybe 9, but definitely not 7. I am a part of the Tacoma Trio who came in after my owner passed away. I am so grateful for a place to stay, but I am now ready for a home to call my own. 

I am good with other dogs and still have a lot of play in me. Oh wait, before I get into all the ways in which I am the perfect dog for you, I must tell you something first. I am intact, meaning I still have the “family jewels” if you know what I mean. This is not usual practice to adopt an intact pup from rescue, but it is in my best interest. My heart might not handle the anesthesia well, which would make neutering me a health risk. The decision was made to keep the jewels and find me a good home with someone who would be responsible, who will make sure I don’t have little Whitey’s running around. A fence is a must! 

If you are still reading and I haven’t scared you off, let me tell you all about the qualities that make me perfect for you. Like I mentioned, I am good with other dogs. I am not very vocal, but I do like to bark to get other dogs to chase me. It’s all in good fun. I could be an only dog in my new home but having a playmate would make me very happy. 

I share my toys and food. I am great on a leash and harness and all people love me. Although I have not had any formal training, I do not jump up and I ride in the car like a champ. I am crate trained and potty trained. I don’t love baths, but I tolerate them if I need one. Luckily, white boxers can run through a mud puddle, and if you simply wait a moment, I will turn white again like magic. 

I am one hunky boy and have so much love to give. I have not experienced a lot of things in my life so I may be a little hesitant with new experiences, but with positive reinforcement, I will give you my all. My coat is soft, and I am affectionate. I am just waiting to get together so we can start our future together. If you think I’m the boy for you, please send in an adoption application – https://www.mustluvboxersrescue.com/adopt.

animal.description:
Hi my name is Tamale, cuz I'm a hot one! I’m 3 years old and 10 lbs! I will need a home without kids. I am a little thing that will need time to adjust in a new environment. I’m a little nervous when you go to touch me with your hands ( AND WILL BITE YOU), but I like when you run your toes on me (see video). So far the bes trick with Tamale is to leave a leash on him at all times so you can "handle him" without really touching him. He i smore like a cat.. and only wants to be touched on his own terms.

Jan 20, 2021 - I bit a volunteer on the hand when they went to take the leash off my collar.

You can come adopt me or even join our foster program to help the humans learn all the awesome things about new dogs like me! Learn more on our website! 

Hope to see you soon! 

What breed am I? Mixed mutt! ODHS does not breed label (unless there’s official paperwork), as studies show it is nearly impossible to tell the exact breed of each dog based off of their appearance.

Educational articles:
3/3/3 Rule;
https://www.rescuedogs101.com/bringing-new-dog-home-3-3-3-rule/?fbclid=IwAR2iv5m7fqk3FieO7LOsstGeGsYYV_F1rJOd1BPxaImofLpcinpYsUbFRWs

Adoption Donations are $250 for an adult, $350 for puppies (a dog under one year of age), and $125 for a senior dog (based on the age of the dog). Adoption donations are to be made via cash, and credit/debit card. There is a $5 fee to run cards.

Please remember to bring a collar and leash (non-retractable) with you the day of the adoption. Note: Martingale collars and slip leads are strongly recommended.

Due to COVID19, we aren't having as many open, public adoption events.  Current schedule is pre-determined meet and greet appointments are Wednesday evenings and on Saturdays. 
Our adoption center is located at 3602 Lafayette Blvd, Suite 102, Fredericksburg, VA 22408. It's important that you keep an eye on your emails for any changes or updates during the adoption process.

Visit our website for an application to adopt. 
https://www.olddominionhumanesociety.org/adoption-application

Old Dominion Humane Society is a volunteer based organization. We are run completely by volunteers, who also have full time jobs, so we appreciate your patience.  Currently, the average timeframe for a response to your application is 1 week.

Like us on Facebook "Old Dominion Humane Society"
and be a part of promoting forever homes for dogs in need.
#Adopt #Donate #Foster #Volunteer 

Note: ODHS only adopts to Virginia and surrounding states (including D.C.). A $50 out of state fee applies.

animal.description:
Eros is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Eros is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~ 1-2yr
Weight: ~ 45lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Eros does best being confined to one area, he will cry a bit (20mins+) but settles down eventually. He would do best in a home that has thick walls/won't have noise complaints.
Dog sociability: Unknown at this time - may be selective, and prefer a small friend circle. On walks he is leash reactive and barks/lunges at other dogs.
Cat sociability: Unknown
Kids: Not recommended for a home with kids. Eros is working on some stranger danger.
Ideal home: Eros would prefer a lowkey household in a lowkey neighborhood. He'd love to work on becoming a more confident dog and would love an adopter excited to work on training!

Eros is such a loving, good boy who only wants to hang out with his human(s). Oddly, his favorite part of the day is training time, because he loves getting rewarded with tasty treats and is quick to learn new skills. He's an energetic pup, but is happy to nap the day away or entertain himself with toys while his human is busy. But make sure you don't skip cuddle time after work; he lives for it! He is a bit timid of new people and prefers slower introductions with high value treats. Walks can be a bit overstimulating for him so he prefers quiet/residential side streets or if you've got a yard even better! Your day won't be complete without Eros' curious head-tilts and tippy-tappy paws, and you won't get enough of looking into those beautiful eyes.

Eros is heartworm positive and will be undergoing treatment at our Ellis Veterinary Clinic. OTAT will cover the cost of his treatment until he is heartworm negative. He is currently in the Doxy phase of his treatment and will be due for injections on these dates: Injection 1 - 2/10/2020
Injections 2 & 3 - 3/12 & 3/13. For information on the heartworm treatment process, visit: onetail.org/heartworm

Eros' adoption fee is 300. He will be neutered on a future date and a 50 refundable neuter deposit will be required. He is up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm positive.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***"

animal.description:
Gobi is being fostered in Ohio. See what his foster mom has to say about Gobi below:

Gobi is outgoing and loves every single person he meets. He is happy, energetic, playful and affectionate. He loves to cuddle and charms every person he meets. He's very curious and adventurous. He just loves life.

He's incredibly cute and has the most expressive ears.

Gobi is very smart and good at getting around. He can go up stairs and jump up on things, but is too nervous to go down stairs. He can follow noises VERY well!

Gobi loves his own name - he lights up whenever he hears it. He's the only dog I've ever met who I would describe as "charismatic." There's just something about him that people fall in love with him instantly.

This little dog was starving as a stray when he was found in Baton Rouge, and he shows signs of having been abused in the past. His positive attitude is all the more inspiring. He's a little survivor.

Gobi is currently being treated for heartworm.
BDRA has voted against the use of electrical fencing effective immediately.

Arenya is a 1.5 year old abused German shepherd . It took us months before we could win her trust but with a lot of patience and lots of treats we gained her trust . 

Arenya snapped and was clearly over and over beaten on her face . X-rays were taken to see if she had no injuries but she was cleared out . 

She is now ready to a forever home with a GERMAN SHEPHERD EXPERIENCED OWNER . 

She is an alpha female and can be dominant . SHe does not like other dogs or cats .  Adopter can not have children or having children on the property . 

Adopter will be checked out by our trainer and has to follow a few training lessons BEFORE we adopt out . This is to protect HER . 

We only want SERIOUS adopters who are willing to give her trust and patience . Potential adopter has to understand that a snap still can happen. SHe did not do it for months now . 

Arenya is located in Middle Island . 

To become her new family please contact us and we will send you the adoption application . 

Every non serious application will be ignored

animal.description:
Sally is a remarkable 2 year old American Pit Bull Terrier and Boxer mix in need of a new home. Sally was surrendered to the shelter with her baby when their family suffered the loss of their home in a house fire. Sally is very sweet, kind and gentle but is quite strong on a leash. She does much better when walked with a harness, but will require some work on this. Sally enjoys being in the company of her people and doesn't seem to mind other dogs so far.

To view the adoptable dogs at our shelter, you must fill out an adoption application found on our website. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, we are showing dogs on an appointment only basis. Please understand that we are receiving a high volume of applications at this time and are doing our best to address as many as we can. Please be patient. Thank you.

The adoption fee for adult dogs is $250. Aside from the shelter, food and water, exercise and compassion they receive while in our care, this also includes veterinary services such as Rabies, Distemper+Lepto, Bordetella, H3N2/H3N8 Influenza, heartworm testing, fecal exams, preventions and deworming medications. Spays/Neuters are also included as part of the adoption fee as is microchipping. 
Puppies under the age of 6 months have an adoption fee of $350. The veterinary services rendered include puppies first round of vaccines, fecal exams, deworming medications, preventions, and microchipping. Our facility spays and neuters dogs at 6 months of age. If the puppy is adopted prior to his, or her prescheduled surgery date, a $200 spay/neuter deposit will be taken on the day of adoption. This deposit it refundable and will be returned to the adopter once proof of the procedure is returned to the shelter. 
COVID-19 NOTE: Please understand that we are looking for forever home for our pets. We understand that many people have a lot of time on their hands during the COVID-19 pandemic, so this may seem like an ideal time to bring home a new pet. Please be sure you are prepared to give your new pet his, or her forever home once our lives go back to normal. They deserve it. Thank you and stay safe.

animal.description:
Greetings from Daisy! 

"Hi everyone! Foster Mommy is taking good care of me! My tail has been wagging more and more every day I've been in foster care. My two tortie sisters are great company! We don't play, but I like watching them run and play and move around the house. I decided to not play with any toys, but I LOVE my new stuffed white bunny! It's a bunny that my tortie sister Lucy used to play with, and Lucy said I could have it. Sometimes I take bunny in my mouth and flip her in the air a few times! I love all the food I'm eating! It's boiled turkey and chicken breast, and LOTS of cooked veggies such as carrots, green beans, sweet potato, and cauliflower, with a few chunks of my dry food at each meal. Every morning I get a half or an entire banana mixed with half can of wet food and of course my cosequin. I look like I've lost some weight already! I feel great and sometimes on our walks I start to trot. I know how to sit and Mommy is teaching me other things like "let's go left and "turn right to see if I can learn those. (I can! I'm very intelligent and she knows!) I LOVE meeting people on our walks, even kids! I already know which house is ours and walk up the driveway on my own. Mommy tried to give me a bath in the shower two nights ago. I refused and laid down on the floor. Mommy said it's ok and she also said it makes sense because she knows I do NOT like getting wet in the rain, so she's going to rub me and brush me with a little baking soda. Aaaahhhh yesssss I love being brushed! Ok, that's all for now. It's time for another nap. I think I'll snore extra loud today! 

With Love, Daisy

animal.description:
Josie is a one-year-old lab/boxer mix. She weighs about 60-65 pounds.  Josie is potty trained and loves to get outside and run. She rides well in the car and isn't a big chewer. Her favorite pastimes are playing tug-of-war and fetch. Josie would do best if she is the only dog in a home, but would be ok with another submissive dog.  She likes being queen of the castle.  Josie is deaf, however, she does seem to hear loud noises.  She knows several signs such as sit, down, come, stay, no, and free.  Josie needs a fenced yard to keep her safe. She has separation anxiety, so a family who has to leave her alone for more than 3 hours and/or lives in an apartment/townhome would not be a good match. She is not a fan of the crate, but we have been working with her and she is doing very well compared to when she came to us. We are also working on leash training.  She can be a bit pulley, but again has improved since we have been working with her. Josie is a very smart girl who responds to lots of love and affection. If you would like to meet this dog please call Teri at 630-897-7454. The adoption fee is $225.

Adoption fee includes:
- microchip
- spay/neuter
- age appropriate vaccinations: Bordetella, DH(L)PP, rabies
- heartworm preventive & flea/tick preventive

animal.description:
This is Baloo, an approximately 2-year-old male American Bully, became a Misfit in the summer of 2020. Baloo was brought into a local shelter showing signs of severe neglect. He was covered in ticks, had untreated entropion in both eyes, and was starved to the point of being skin and bones. Baloo is neutered, up to date on all age-appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, heartworm negative, and micro-chipped. 

He is house trained. He does not use a kennel but would probably be fine in one. He needs some work on leash manners but loves going for walks! He enjoys going for rides in the car, too.

Baloo knows how to sit and is learning touch. He is a quick learner who can easily be trained for more commands. Due to the nature of his past neglect, he's a big fan of food. He will do just about anything for food or treats. But he doesn't want to share so make sure he's always fed in his own safe space where no other pets might intrude. 

Baloo lives with a 1-year-old child in his foster home and loves him very much. He has done well with kids of all ages. Due to his energy level and size, please use caution around smaller kids so that he doesn't accidentally knock them over. 

We don't know for sure if Baloo likes cats but we can guess that he would like to chase them. Baloo loves to play with other dogs but it's important that they can tolerate his energy level. He doesn't always recognize cues to slow down or take it easy. Therefore he does best with very friendly and playful dogs, but he doesn't mesh as well with dogs who are more dominant or assertive.

Baloo is a happy-go-lucky guy with a real zest for life. His giant ears are one of his best characteristics. We love to watch them move around like satellites as he listens to everything around him.

Baloo is so well-behaved in the house that he has never been kenneled at his foster home. He is one of the best dogs we've ever had the joy of fostering. He goes to the door and barks when he needs to potty and he barks when he's ready to come back inside.

Baloo enjoys sunbathing outside at times but his favorite spot is curled up on the couch. He enjoys playing fetch and tug of war. Squeaky toys bring him so much joy. He is the perfect mix of laid back and playful. He usually has a daily burst of energy that involves playing with his toys and zooming around the yard. Then the rest of the day is spent snoozing in a soft spot, preferably cuddled up with a human.

Baloo is not a 'guard dog' type and rarely even gets up when someone comes in the front door. He's just a lover and will be the best snuggle buddy you've ever known. 

To meet/adopt Baloo, go to http://muttmisfits.com/adoption-application/

Meet Raisin Bran! 

His muzzle maybe gray but he has a lot of life left in him. Raisin Bran is an easy fellow to care for. He likes an occasional walk but then likes to rest. If he can rest in your lap that would be even better. Raisin Bran would like a quiet home so no children. He gets along with his doggie friends but is fine being solo. Do you have it in your heart to give him his retirement home?

Interested in meeting Raisin Bran? 

All Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue dogs are in homes with foster families; we do not have a shelter where dogs are available for daily viewing.

Our process is as follows:
1.  Review our policies and adoption radius  on our website: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/
2.  Submit an application for review and approval;
3.  MPM Rescue reviews application and checks vet records and references;
4.  MPM foster contacts approved applicant(s) to arrange a home check and meeting with available dog(s);
5.   If there is a good fit, adoption is completed with a contract and fees (payable via check or cash).

The adoption fee is listed here: http://mapawsmepetrescue.com/adopt/

Dogs from Ma, Paws & Me Pet Rescue come with the following medical care already provided:
- Spay/Neuter surgery
- Age appropriate vaccinations
- Heartworm test (for dogs over 6mo) and treatment if positive
- Microchip
- Deworming
- Heartworm and Flea/Tick Preventative
- Any other necessary medical treatment as recommended by veterinarian

*Please note that the identified breed(s) are best guesses. We very rarely have information on our dogs' actual breeds since they often come to the shelters we work with as strays.*

animal.description:
Meet Frankie, an approximately 10-year-old male miniature pinscher who became a Misfit when he and his four sisters were surrendered to a local shelter after their human died. This pet is neutered, up to date on all age-appropriate vaccinations and preventatives, heart-worm negative, and micro-chipped!

When Frankie came to his foster parents, he was confused, sick, and neglected.  This was very stressful for him, and even more so, since he had to be kept quarantined because he had an upper respiratory infection (URI).  When he was let out of his crate, all he would do is run in circles.  When he was put back in his crate, he would spin in circles for hours until he wore himself out and fell asleep. When he was cleared of his URI, he was allowed to roam the house with his foster brothers.  After about two weeks he acclimated and began acting more normal.  He is mostly deaf but can hear very loud noises.  When he is awake, he follows humans everywhere hoping it is time for food.

Frankie is good with dogs of all sizes.  He hasn’t been around cats or children.  We don’t think he would be a good fit with anyone elderly, or who is not stable on their feet, as he likes to run around and step on top of your feet as you walk.

Frankie is not potty trained, but he will use the doggie door to go in and out.  He uses the same place in the house to potty every time on potty pads.  He gets super excited after he does his business and has to run through the house.

He doesn’t have a lot of teeth, but he eats a mixture of wet food and small dry kibble.  He isn’t big on treats, but when his brothers get their treats, he will always be willing to accept a Ritz cracker or a piece of cheese.

You can apply to meet/adopt this pet at www.muttmisfits.com/adoption-application.

animal.description:
BACKSTORY:
Gotti was surrendered to an area animal control when his owner moved and couldn’t take him with him. One of our interaction team members was there on the very day he was surrendered and committed to getting him out because animal control is no place for any dog, let alone a 9-year-old boy.

He was very sick with an antibiotic-resistant upper respiratory infection and suspected bladder infection so he was put into isolation and we weren’t able to bust him out. We checked on him regularly and kept asking when we could take him.

Finally, 3 months later the animal control vet said we were able to take him. and we couldn’t have been more excited to have this guy leave the building and be in a loving supportive foster home and out of a cage.

Unfortunately, the suspected urinary infection was looking like it was way more than that. Gotti was leaking urine and blood every time he moved. His hindquarters were lethargic and tender to the touch and he had swelling in his anal area. He was rushed to our vet who diagnosed a severe prostate infection that had probably been going on for an extremely long time, long enough that they thought he might have cancer. Luckily, it wasn't cancer, just the infection!

He is a bit slow going when first getting up and has some tenderness in his hindquarters which the vet said is arthritis and the doctors are confident in saying that Gotti will get better once he builds more muscle.

EDUCATION:
* Sit
* Touch
* House trained

ACTIVITIES THIS CUTIE ENJOYS:
* Treats: goat cheese, peanut butter, Grandma Lucy's cookie treats
* Food: he likes Stella & Chewy
* Toys: hasn't shown interest in toys
* Walks: pulls hard the entire walk
* Cuddling
* Sleeping
* Chin & ear scratches
* Calm walks in the yard
* Lots of petting!
* He just wants to hang out

SKILLS:
* Dogs: friendly
* Kids: friendly
* People: friendly
* Cats: unknown

CHALLENGES:
* Will do best in a home without stairs
* Can be mouthy at times
* When bored, he's been known to chew on throw blankets
* He is a destroyer of dog beds!

animal.description:
Meet Dolly!

Hard to believe that this lovely, lively, friendly little goofball is still available for adoption.  And yet, here she is...  To her chagrin, the uncontainable excitement that Dolly feels when she meets other dogs is what's most annoying to them.  She shows NO aggression.  She is absolutely WONDERFUL with people of all ages!  Dolly is waiting in Weare, NH for her forever family to come and whisk her away to a better life!  

This gorgeous, gentle girl loves to go for walks, and she walks well on a leash. She has a beautiful, soft tan coat, and she's in perfect shape.  And those amber eyes - just LOVELY!

This sweet baby was on Death Row in a high kill facility in Georgia, and with her innocent, trusting nature, she kissed the hands of those who intended to euthanize her.  

Dolly spent about 2 months in a foster home in GA after leaving the Animal Control facility, so she is well acclimated to living in a family environment.  She is very playful and she just loves to cuddle with her humans.  Her foster mom cried when she left to come to NH.

Dolly is about 1 year old, weighs 48 lbs, has all of her required vaccines, and is spayed and microchipped.

Her medical records indicate that she is a Terrier mix.

If you are interested in adopting this delightful young girl, please complete an adoption application at https://www.heartsandtails.org/adoption-application/.

PLEASE NOTE that due to the overwhelming number of inquiries we receive daily, we can only respond to those who have completed an online application, and appear to be a good match. PLEASE check all of the fields in this profile to ensure your question hasn't already been answered as most of the information is in this profile.

animal.description:
Hey Rusty, it is time your are finally being made active! His foster refers to him as Mr. Snufflupagus.

Huh????? I'm Active??? 

You know me I am not really active kinda of fellow.... I really just enjoy laying on the couch, or laying in the sun or watching my favorite TV shows on the couch with my warm blanket. 

Will this active thing change any of those things ? 

It means it is time for you to find your forever home and find your own family, your own couch and maybe your own TV! 

Oh I think I get what that means... but does this have to happen now .. 

Here is my bio-
I'm an 8 year old boy that likes to wander the back 40.
By back 40. I mean safely fence yard with water and a home to chill out in the sun while you yell for me .... 

You will get a meet and greet them too ... 

I hope it is not during Jeopardy... Seriously I can not miss an episode . 

They will have to reschedule that meet and greet thingy.... 

I'm going through Heartworm treatment right now and they doctor said i must relax on the couch and watch Jeopardy. 

 Holla Rusty!!! And I will meander over. 

This pair of seniors are very bonded. They were surrendered together in a shelter and Hailee would stand under Rusty for protection. They need to be kept together and be allowed to live their lives out with each other. Besties to the end. Rusty is a retriever mix and Hailee is a little chi mix. Rusty just loves exploring in the backyard and lounging in the sun. Hailee found a shady space and laid down and watched her buddy.

animal.description:
King came to our organization a few months ago as a horrible neglect case - initial photo shown above. He has been on medical hold while undergoing multiple procedures, including medicated baths, mass removals, neutering, nail trimmings and professional training. He has come SO far and has many fans (as seen with his biggest Mohawk twin fan, April). 
Now, he is ready to find his forever family that will love him the way he deserved to be loved from day one. 
King is 7 years old, cleared medically, neutered, UTD on vaccines and microchipped. We have been told that he lived with a female dog before, but due to medical reasons, we have not yet dog or cat tested King. Though, from a distance, King seems to prefer smaller low key females. King is very strong, but has a beautiful demeanor. Because of his strength, we would recommend no children under the age of 12. Per our trainer, "someone will get a wonderful dog in King. He is smart, loving and wants to please!" King has really enjoyed his training (as seen kissing his trainer in the photos), and we will be encouraging and requiring his training to continue in his forever home. 
Interested in meeting King? Apply here: https://www.theroadhomeanimalproject.org/companion-adoption-form-pdf.html

*Note: ALL members of the family (canine and human alike) MUST be present for any meet and greet.

animal.description:
Steele – Pit bull mix - 2yrs. - male (58 lbs.)

This handsome boy was surrendered by his owner when the other dog in the home beat him up. Poor Steele ended up wounded, homeless, and in a county shelter. That's where we spotted him and knew we had to have him. Steele was adopted back in September, but the owner wasn't able to give him what he needs: structure and experience. Steele needs to know that someone else is in charge so he doesn't have to be. He bonds quickly to his person and wants to protect them, which means he needs an owner who lets him know THEY are handling things. We’re happy to have Steele back with us. Now we know even more about him and can make sure to find him a home where he thrives. Steele is crazy sweet, has an awesome personality, and loves everyone. He is a bit timid when he first meets new dogs (who could blame him), but in a short time he gains his confidence and does well. He plays with several other dogs and always looks like he's smiling while he's playing. He is not a fan of "crazy play" and prefers dogs that aren't always in his face. He would also do well as an only dog because he loves attention. Steele is housebroken, crate trained, and loves to go for walks. Once on a leash, Steele becomes an adventurer; he's delighted by every turn enjoying the whole experience. Steele is not only adorable, he's smart, sweet, and loves to be close. This boy is going to make some lucky person or family very happy with his unconditional love and devotion. If you think that person could be you, please fill out an application to start the adoption process.

animal.description:
Meet Bella. This adorable Bully girl was rescued by a Good Samaritan who saw her posted on Facebook. Bella had jumped into a social worker's van while working in a rural SC neighborhood, and the woman took her home and posted a plea for help. Apparently, Bella belonged to another family in the neighborhood, but they moved and just left her behind with no plan for her well being. The Good Samaritan responded to the FB post and offered to take Bella until they could find a rescue. She reached out to Worthy Dog for help, and we found a foster home for her who could care for her while she goes through heartworm treatment.

Bella is currently being fostered with a couple and their family dog in Charlotte, NC. She's doing well with the other dog in the home and will be best paired with a calm, confident dog who is close to her in size, or would be fine as an only dog too. NO CATS...We have not seen her around cats, but she does have prey drive around chickens.

This bully girls is a very social dog by nature. On walks, she wants to stop and greet every dog, child, and adult. Her foster family had friends over recently, and she loved everyone there. She may bark when there's an initial knock at the door, but that's just her natural alert instinct. She greets visitors well and is very attached to her people. Her foster mom, Hailey, describes her as confident and snuggly and says she can be a little bossy too. She's housetrained and will typically scratch at the door or bark when she needs to go out. Hailey has not used the crate with her and trusts her to be free to roam in the home when left alone.

Bella has a more moderate energy level. In the house, she is a couch potato who loves to nap under the covers. She enjoys walks too, and is a strong pup who can pull, so she needs a capable handler. Her foster family has been watching her calories, doing regular walks to help her trim down, and she has already lost 2 to 3 lbs. It will be important for her new family to be committed to daily exercise and a healthy diet so that Bella can be her best self.

Hailey shared that Bella is very food motivated and a champion catcher of treats. She loves toys but also wants to destroy them. She can be a little protective of toys if another dog wants to take them away, so that needs to be managed early on. She is always up for a road trip but will try to sit in your lap if you don't contain her, so her foster mom uses a crate for safety. Bella is pretty human-focused and likes to be where you are. She will occasionally go off on her own to bask in a sunny spot near the window or on the back porch, but mostly she's by your side. At night, she would love to share a bed with you if you'll let her, and she is a very snuggly dog!

This sweet girl, with soulful eyes, will make someone a great companion. Apply today to learn more.

Preference will be given to families with some large dog or bully breed experience.

BREED ESTIMATE: APBT or American Bulldog mix
GENDER: Female
APPROXIMATE WEIGHT: 65lbs - (needs to lose 5 lbs)
APPROXIMATE AGE: ~ 3 to 4 years
COAT TYPE: short
ADOPTION FEE: $400
OTHER INFO: utd on shots/spayed/microchipped/treated for heartworm
LOCATION: Alexandria, VA

FOR MORE INFO OR TO ADOPT: Please go to https://adopt.worthydog.org and complete the application.

You can also help save dogs like this one by becoming a foster, providing a rescue dog with a temporary home and giving them the love and care they need until they are permanently adopted. Every person who fosters is directly responsible for saving the life of a dog, because we can only save as many dogs as we have foster families available to welcome them into their homes. If you think you might be interested in becoming a foster and want to learn more, please go to https://foster.worthydog.org and fill out an application.

Worthy Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue that primarily adopts to families in the DC Metro area.

animal.description:
Reisha 'Penny' Sherwood is an approximately 10 month old bloodhound that  currently weighs 65 pounds. 
 
Penny, as we call her, came into our program after being found and no owner ever stepped up to claim her.  For such a young dog she has quite a few stories to tell it seems.  When we took her in we knew she was heart worm positive and had a bum leg....when she got her X-rays it was clear she'd likely been hit by a car early on and had a break that was allowed to heal improperly, but also, like so many southern rescues, she has some "buckshot" in her as well.  None of what she has been through has phased her amazing personality.  There is no limp in her smile!!!  

This sweetheart of a girl has finished her heartworm treatment and is feeling great!  She loves her walks,  inside toys, bones and puzzles.  Penny is actually extremely calm inside the house and loves to lounge around in the sun.  We'd love to find her a fenced yard where she can have a little freedom to work her nose, run and play to her heart's content.  Penny's foster mom has been working her brain with basic obedience.  She is a very smart girl and is working hard and learning!!  She has mastered her sit and stay and is very food/treat motivated. She has learned so much in a month's time!  She loves any interaction with humans and enjoys playing with other dogs.  Penny is a great combination of calm and playful and can also easily entertain herself.  

Reisha 'Penny' Sherwood is up to date on shots and preventatives and is microchipped.    She will be spayed prior to adoption and her adoption fee is $250 plus any additional donation you feel appropriate.  Our adoption fee is set to a level to make adoptions happen.  They do not cover our costs. Thank you for your generosity and interest in our dogs!   

All dogs adopted locally through SGDR receive a free six-week session of obedience classes and a lifetime of behavior support through our Project REWARD program with trainer Charlotte Blake.

You must have an approved application before being able to visit a dog. Visit our website below for an adoption application https://www.snootygiggles.com/dog-application/

If you expect to leave the dog alone for long periods of time, please do not consider adopting a puppy.  Puppies need lots of attention and companionship.  Thanks.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.
animal.name: Reisha "Penny" Sherwood

animal.description:
Say hello to Lady! This sweet senior is ready to find her forever retirement home!

This sweet girl is 7 years young and 49 pounds. Her beautiful and sensitive eyes will lure you in. And her absolutely sweet temperament will make you fall in love.

Lady is the easiest couch potato you’ll ever encounter. Lady just wants to live a simple life with lots of snacks, naps, and cuddles from her very own human(s). She loves snuggle time on the couch. Lady is super easy on leash and even enjoys her kennel, as long as she gets her own soft blanket and bed. 

She is very dog friendly and gets along well with both males and females. She is lower energy and would likely do best in a home with a dog with a similar energy level. Lady would do best in a home without cats. She would do well with children who are respectful of her space. We don't know Lady's history but she can be a little skittish at times. 

If you’re looking to adopt an incredible senior dog, Lady truly deserves a retirement home that will love her for the rest of her days. Lady has Cushing's Disease and will need to be on daily medication for the remainder of her life.  Although she’s less than perfect, this gal makes up for all of it with her sweet personality! She is Miss Congeniality for sure, and deserves a retirement home that will pamper her the way she deserves!

If interested in meeting Lady, please email adoption@sdsanctuary.com.

animal.description:
Red Robin is a handsome guy about 10-12 months old, 33 pounds, tested heartworm negative and is now current on all his vaccines and preventatives.  He’s a bit on the shy side but warms up quickly. He did very well for his test and his shots. 
Red is scheduled for his neuter Wednesday, January 27th and will get his microchip at that time.
He was a stray in Memphis (11-28) and no owner has come forward. He still needs to be neutered and get a microchip. He gets along with other dogs and is very active. Looks to have some Australian shepherd in him.  His fury coat is very very soft!  His foster dad is working on house training and leash walking.  He gets along fine with the other two dogs in his foster home but has too much energy for the older dogs.  He is trying to herd them but nipping at their heels. He would do best in a home with a younger dog that also has a lot of energy to burn off.  He also needs a fenced in yard to play and exercise in safely.
His adoption fee is $150 and includes his neuter and microchip.

If you are interested in adopting, we encourage you to fill out our adoption questionnaire at http://members.petfinder.com/~MS72/adoption_app.html

Save 1 Pet is a 501 (c) 3 approved charity committed to helping homeless animals.  We don't have a facility (shelter) but work out of our homes to foster the animals until they find a forever home.

Please be advised that for all adoptions, we will conduct reference checks, including veterinary references.  Our adoption fee for dogs includes spay/neuter, heart worm check, current vaccines, microchip, worming and heart worm/flea/tick prevention.
For dog adoptions, we do conduct fence verification.
When adopting an animal, you will be asked to complete our Adoption Contract

animal.description:
Remmy has been in the program for 4 weeks now and has 4 more weeks to go. He is a fun, playful pup who enjoys people and other dogs. His ideal new home will have plenty of room for him to run and lots of activities to keep him busy.
11/20/2020--Remmy is currently housed and enrolled in the Puppies for Parole Program at the Boonville Correction Center where (s)he will stay for 8 weeks of basic obedience training. (S)He will learn commands such as “sit”, “stay”, “heel”, “come”, etc. (S)He will learn crate and house training. Remmy will be available for adoption while (s) he is in the Program, but will not be released to his/her new adopting family until the end of the 8 weeks when (s)he graduates. The adoption fee for a Puppies for Parole dog is $100. For questions regarding adoptions, call the Marshall Animal Shelter at (660)831-0420
11/2/2020--Remmy has a story to tell! Before he was surrendered by his family, they gave him to a friend who lived 15 miles away from their home. Remmy left his new owner and ran the 15 miles back home! Unfortunately, his family still was unable to keep him due to moving so they signed him over to the shelter. Remmy has been with the same family and their children all of his life so change is a little rough for him at first. He will bark at strangers, but also want to greet them.

animal.description:
Leo and Apollo are a male, bonded pair who are about 3-4 years old. 

These brothers are extremely shy at first and need a nice quiet home. 
They have been known to fear bite - especially Leo - so a home with no kids is a must. 

After only a day, Apollo is giving kisses to his foster mom. They need someone who understands their scaredy-ness and goes slow with them.

They have really come out of their shells in their foster home. No more grumbles. 
They are good with other dogs and are really bonded to each other. 
That could be part of the reason they were acting out initially because they were surrendered to different shelters. 

**No small kids

**These boys are bonded and will only be adopted together. 
Can we find them a happy ending for Christmas? 

Leo and Apollo are currently being fostered in Clarksville, Tn.

animal.description:
Sammy was rescued off the streets of Corpus Christi Texas. He had been abandoned as a young puppy, along with his mom and siblings.
Over time, Sammy and her one sister (Elizabeth--also for adoption) were the only ones left. Their mom—and other siblings—disappeared and probably either starved to death or were hit by cars.

Fortunately, Sammy and Elizabeth escaped that fate—although Sammy did sustain a serious leg injury during his time living on the streets.
(His leg has since healed--although not correctly--and he tends to want to walk on the top of his foot which is causing him to develop a sore. At this time we are considering possible leg amputation, but--rest assured--—"tripods" get around just fine and having three legs will not slow him down a bit!)

Our best guess is that Sammy is a little less than a year of age. With good food and a de-worming regimen, he now weighs 38 lbs. (although he was much thinner when the video was taken). 

We really have no idea what mix of breeds Sammy is, but he is a very sweet dog who always seems to have a smile on his face! He is extremely gentle and he does well with other dogs and people. 

Sammy needs a home with another dog for companionship, and he would benefit from attending obedience classes to learn the basic commands. (But he is VERY smart--and he wants to please--so he should be a star student!)

A large safely fenced yard is a must for Sammy (we do not consider an "invisible" fence as a safe way to contain a dog). Also, we would prefer he goes to an adopter who won’t leave him home for extended periods of time, so an owner who works at home or only works part time would be ideal.

Sammy will be neutered soon, so at adoption he will have been totally vetted (including immunizations, de-worming, heartworm test, and microchip).
His adoption fee is $300 (which includes the amputation which we will have done along with being neutered.)

If you are interested in adopting Sammy, please e-mail us at: sylvialovesme@gmail.com and tell us a little about yourself and your living situation. Then, if we all agree that you might be a good fit for each other, we will send you an adoption application. And once your application is returned and reviewed, we can schedule a meet-and-greet.

He becomes very whiney when he wants something or when he is uncomfortable which we are working to correct.Good at alerting.

Because of his insecurity issues, it is NOT recommended that Jager is around children or adults who are not able to pick up on his cues. animal.description:
Elizabeth was rescued off the streets of Corpus Christi Texas. As a puppy, she had been abandoned by her owner, along with her mom and siblings.
Over time, Elizabeth and her one brother Sammy--also available for adoption--were the only ones left. Their mom—and other siblings—disappeared and either starved to death or were hit by cars.  :-(

Fortunately, Elizabeth and her brother Sammy escaped that fate and now they are both ready to start a new and happy life with a loving family!
Elizabeth weighs about 35 lbs. (she is pretty much full grown).
She is a very sweet dog who loves people and does well with other dogs. 

We are looking for an adopter who has another dog (a dog her size or larger would be best). And because she has so much energy, a large safely fenced yard is a must (please note: we do not consider an "invisible" fence to be a safe way to contain a dog). 

We would prefer she goes to an adopter who won’t leave her home for extended periods of time, so an owner who works at home or only works part time would be ideal.  Elizabeth would benefit from attending obedience class to learn the basics of good manners (she has a tendency to want to jump up on people for attention) but she is a quick learner and wants to please.

Elizabeth is totally vetted (spayed, immunizations, de-worming, heartworm test, and microchip) and her adoption fee is $300.

If you are interested in adopting Elizabeth, please e-mail us at: sylvialovesme@gmail.com and tell us a little about yourself and your living situation. Then, if we all agree that you might be a good fit for each other, we will send you an adoption application. And once your application is returned and reviewed, we can schedule a meet-and-greet.
