animal.description: Sweet mama Arkansas is around 2 years old and looks to be a Lab and Shepherd mix. She was rescued with her 10 puppies from a farm that had too many dogs and couldn't properly care for her and her pups. Now she is ready to put parenthood behind her in favor of a home of her own. She is a little shy at first so she's looking for a kind and patient family that will continue working on her socialization and build her confidence. She is doing wonderfully in her foster home where she has conquered the stairs, started to play with toys and even snoozes on the couch. She's even house trained! She is still working on "outside" things like walks and not freezing up when she sees unfamiliar people or dogs. Arkansas needs a mellow household with an owner who understands shy dogs and is willing to put in the extra energy and training to help her blossom into the best dog that she can be. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Arkansas, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting this dog, please download and complete an Adoption Questionnaire from our website and email Dena at DenaE@k-9lifesavers.org

You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.

Dog's Name: Freddie

Estimated Breed : Pointer Mix

Approximate Age: 1 yr.

Approximate Weight: approx. 55 lbs

Currently Living at: Foster

Adoption Fee: $300

DOG'S DESCRIPTION

This amazing boy should be known as Superdog, the three-legged-wonder! Determined not to let anything like a missing front leg slow him down, Freddie lives life to the fullest and loves nothing more than playing with other energetic dogs and attention from his humans. Best friends with everyone, he would love a family to show him lots of love. Freddie will do best in an adult only home, or teenage children would be fine as well. He does great with another energetic dog to romp around with and/or someone home most of the time. He's doing better in foster care and getting used to the routine but loves his humans so much he wants to be around getting attention all the time. He loves to snuggle in the big bed, but is getting used to a crate. He is housetrained but expect a couple accidents at first while learning the new routine.

Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.

Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.

Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org

Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!

For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.

Please "like" our
Facebook Page
for the most current events and new dogs.

Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
BUDDY IS IN A FOSTER HOME

Date of birth:  11/2018

12/22/2020:  Buddy is a super cute Lab/Hound mix! He’s 2 years old and weighs 50 lbs, but he needs to put on more weight and could easily weigh 60+. Buddy is a little shy at first, but he’s very sweet natured.  He warms up quickly and then enjoys attention and being petted.

• Buddy would like a home with a fenced yard and another doggie friend. He lives in a foster home with other dogs and puppies and gets along extremely well with all. He’d be a wonderful companion for another dog. We’ll ask you to bring your dog to meet Buddy to see if they could be friends.

• Buddy is pretty mellow and gentle and likes relaxing in the sun.

• Because he’s a little timid, we don’t want to place Buddy in a home with young kids. But he’d be fine with older kids/teens. 

• Buddy has a doggie door in his foster home and he is house trained and crate trained.  

• He’s not a big barker and doesn’t jump the fence.  

• Unfortunately, Buddy has heartworms. He will be starting treatment on January 11. He’ll need to be restricted to limited activity for several weeks after that— but he’s not a high energy guy so that shouldn’t be terribly difficult.  We can fill you in more about his treatment plan if you’re interested in fostering or adopting Buddy.

• Buddy was originally in a shelter in rural Arkansas.  His time was up there, so we transferred him (and other dogs) up here so that we could treat his heartworms and find him a loving home. He’s a real sweetie!

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info. 

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:

Phone: 913.521.2339

Your deposit is returned after the animal is spayed/neutered. All animals adopted from the shelter MUST be spayed/neutered. Dogs arriving at the shelter receive DA2PP and Bordetella. Cats receive a vaccine for Rhinotracheitis-Calici-Panleukopenia-Chlamydia Psittaci. The animals at our shelter have been picked up stray. Please remember this when requesting additional information about the animals. Questions can be emailed to emporiakansasanimalshelter@gmail.com

animal.description:
Bosley comes to rescue from TX as a stray.  He is just a puppy born 8.6.2020. He is a very mellow, handsome, young guy. His adoption fee is $350. He is very laid back loves to curl up and sleep.  He's playful with lots of energy.  He has only had a few accidents with foster in MN as they get to know him.  He does know to go to the door to let folks know he needs to go out.  

1.22.21 update:   He is excellent with kids. I would say any age. He has learned "kennel up"  and will run into the kennel for feeding time, no need to say anything, he just knows what to do. Sometimes when he is just plan tired, he goes in his kennel for naps without me telling him. He is very submissive, I think a dog that will help boost his confidence would benefit him, but he could be a single dog household too. 

He is 100% potty trained and will bark if in his kennel to go outside or ring the bell on my back door if he needs to go out. 

When he gets playing, his zoomies are hilarious to watch, but his prancing and movements make me wonder if he grew up with a heard of horses! He does great in the leash, he does need a reminder in the beginning, but he normally doesn't pull unless a smell catches his nose on a tree. He still is learning to not jump up to look on the counters or table top but a simple Bosley down and he listens. 

If someone is looking a dog who will go out for adventures or just snuggle up on the couch and take naps, Bosley is the boy for them! He truly is a good boy especially under the circumstances he came from.

12.29.21 update:
He does great in a kennel and sleeps through the nite.  At night he will bat his cute puppy eyes at foster mom to stay up longer.  As a puppy he does not know what are legal toys or items like shoes etc.  He will put anything in his mouth but easy to teach the difference.  We do require a 6' fenced yard to adopt this dog.

He is learning sit, down, leave it, and stay but catches on quickly.  Leash training is coming.  We do not allow our dogs to be tied, tethered, chained or confined to any form of a tie out. We do not adopt to folks that have underground fence system.  For serious inquiries go to www.faerielandrescue.org to apply.

animal.description:
Lucky Momma is the dog everyone wants to come home to. She does need a bit of time to warm up, but when she is settled and happy her greetings are full body wiggles! She is a fantastic playmate, a great study buddy for calm oldeir kids, or a warm couch cuddler after work. Lucky mama will require a fenced yard. Share also learns quickly and wants to please her humans. She does get scared of rambunctious kids, loud men, or noises and would prefer a home with another dog, to show her the way. She was rescued from a home with many many dogs and is much more comfortable with a dog in the home. 

She is house & crate trained and has even recently been introduced to cats and has done fantastic. Lucky Momma rides fine in the car but she is not a big fan and will alternate between sitting and lying down often. She doesn't know many commands yet, but behaves perfectly inside, even handles nail trims like a pro. Come dinner time she will do anything under the sun to get that food bowl to come down faster. Lucky Momma has a funny affinity for finding stray socks and prancing around with her find, but she has never chewed anything up. She is approximately 3-4 years old and a medium sized girl at ~40lbs. with a unique coat pattern. Meet this perfect gal today.

Adoption fee for all dogs and puppies is $300. Dirt Road Doggies are fully vetted, on heartworm prevention, fixed, and microchipped. Puppies under 6 months are adopted under a spay/neuter contract which is covered when using our vet. DRDR is a foster-based rescue with dogs residing in homes mainly around NE GA with regular adoption events at Petco Dacula. We adopt within a 3 hour driving distance of Gainesville, GA. Apply to meet any DRDR dog here: https://petlover.petstablished.com/pets/public/895758

animal.description:
Watch out, Bandit is here to steal your heart (and all your snacks)! If those ears don't do the trick, his eyes certainly will!

This guy has come a long way from when he came to us in the beginning of October 2020. Bandit was taken by animal control from his original home where he lived with six other dogs (his parents and siblings) in a pen outside. Living that way for his entire puppyhood has made life a challenge for Bandit but he has been working on getting used to normal dog things. 

Bandit absolutely LOVES other dogs and has no trouble jumping right into a play session. He is most comfortable when other dogs are around to help give him clues on how to react. Bandit also has a lot of experience living around cats. He likes to try and play and will chase them if they run but quickly jumps away and leaves them alone if they swat at him or walk/jump away.

His foster home has spent lots of time working one-on-one with Bandit to increase his confidence on his own and around people, which is his biggest weakness. Bandit is incredibly uncomfortable with close contact and handling from people. His new family will need to respect that and give him time and space to come around when he is ready. 

Bandit is quite a goofball once he gest comfortable! He gets excited to go outside with his foster mom and will hop around and play chase with her on leash. He likes to play "find it" with treats and food out in the grass. His foster homes have focused on teaching him to be a dog and giving him coping skills to help him adapt to life in a home around people.

Bandit's ideal home is one with exceptionally patient and understanding humans who are willing to continue positive reinforcement training and safe socialization at his pace. Because of Bandit's behavioral needs, he is eligible for a foster to adopt situation. Interested parties should fill out an adoption application and if approved, can take him home as a foster dog to get a true sense of his needs before finalizing his adoption.

He currently weighs around 45lbs and will be neutered in the coming weeks. He is up to date on vaccines and parasite prevention.

animal.description:
This Aly will be your forever ally!

Hey hey! My name is Aly and I am a young, 2 year old, female spayed Lab mix. I am about 41 lbs and come with the typical Lab goodies of cuddles and playfulness. I was rescued from Mexico, where I have had an FHO surgery to stabilize my hip. I am chilling out at my foster home and learning to be a great dog! I am fully house trained and pretty good on the leash. There may be a bit of pulling when I see other dogs, but tasty treats and positive reinforcement will get the job done! My surgery has helped me walk around with more ease and has even given me a cute dancing style. It has limited my jumping though, so I require assistance while getting in and out of cars and some coaxing for the stairs. But the good thing is, it has made me timid about jumping on couch or beds!

I am an affectionate, friendly gal who loves to shower her people with love. I do enjoy playing with other dogs, but I don't quite like living with other female dogs. There can be only one queen, right?! I enjoy being off-leash at the park and playing with my furry friends. On leash, I can be a bit reactive, but mostly because I want to play! Don't go by my bark, its just more sound than anything. Actually, I am a timid gal and hence, I get nervous and bark. I am also quite vigilant and like to watch out for my family. I don't think cats and I will get along too well. I have not been around kids yet! I let my family cuddle me all day because they love my soft skin and ears! They say I am actually quite intelligent and will pick training up quite quickly!

I would love a loving family who trains me with patience and plenty of positive reinforcement to make me the best lady around! I would like more socialization to help me understand that other dogs can be very fun! I am mellow, with playful bouts, and eager to please. I pawmise to give velvety cuddles to let you squeeze me! If you think that we could be the perfect allies, give me a woof! My adoption fee is $400 and that includes spaying/neutering, shots, and microchip. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here https://theanimalpad.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Roxbury/Roxie arrived at the Nacogdoches Animal Shelter on August 24, 2020. She spent 119 days in the shelter before NorthStar was able to find a foster for her as large dog fosters, especially for heartworm positive dogs, are hard to come by.

During her time at the shelter, Roxie gave birth to a single puppy. No one even realized Roxie was pregnant because she was so small - people thought she was just getting a little chubby due to her very healthy appetite! Roxie gave birth to Pebble on October 17th and was the best mother. She always made sure her little pebble was clean, had a full tummy, and was always kept warm. She would even bring the food bowl into the bed with them as she got older. Once Pebble turned 7 weeks old, she was placed into foster home in Texas so that she could make her way to NorthStar. Roxie obviously missed her, but we knew that away from the shelter was the safest place for her pup.

Roxie is the goofiest pup! She is about 3 years old and will soon start heartworm treatment and be spayed. She is a Black Mouth Cur mix who weighs about 45 pounds. She very rarely barks, doesn't use the bathroom in her kennel if given the choice, and follows directions very well - she goes into her kennel with the point of a finger and a whistle!

Roxie often gets a case of the zoomies and sprints in large circles around her humans. She adores toys and can be found squeaking her toys and throwing them up in the air to entertain herself. She is always happy; I've never seen her not excited to be alive! She runs with her head tilted back and her tail to the ground as if to build up speed. She doesn't do anything half speed. We have enjoyed every moment with her!

Once Roxie makes her way to NJ, she will be looking for a wonderful forever home with people who will love her & enjoy her company. If you'd like to meet Roxie when she arrives, please fill out an application at www.northstarpets.org & ask for ROXBURY NAC!

Here is more about Kuzco!

3-year-old, 60-pound Hound mix
House-Trained / Crate-Trained

Other Dogs: Not a dog park candidate, does not get along with male dogs, would be okay with a female dog with slow introductions.
Cats: No, has some prey drive.  
Kids: Unknown, no exposure while in foster care. 

Kuzco is a sweet and friendly pup who loves his humans and receiving affection! He is working on some of his manners and his adoptive human(s) should plan to continue this training so he can be his best self. His foster is also working with him on his anxiety around men in uniform e.g., delivery personnel, mail carriers. 

Kuzco enjoys chasing tennis balls, playing with stuffed animal toys, and nose-work games; he has an extraordinary sense of smell! He also loves going for walks, food, and mental enrichment toys like stuffed Kongs, puzzles or fetch. 

Kuzco would love to have a fenced yard to play in and because he is an excellent jumper, it would need to be at least six feet tall; however, if he is getting other daily exercise, he does not need one.  

Kuzco would love a home where he feels he is an important part of his human(s) lives filled with lots of snuggles, couch time, exercise, and adventures. 


His adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm/Lyme test, all age-appropriate vaccinations (distemper, rabies, & Bordetella), HW and flea/tick preventative, and microchip implant and registration. 

There is no guarantee of age and breed as a rescue animal's history is unknown. All ages and breeds are best guess.

Adoption fees INCLUDE a mandatory sales tax of 7.525%.

Due to post-adoption services provided, it is Pet Haven's policy to only place dogs into homes within a 150-mile radius of the Minneapolis, MN city center.

animal.description:
Cayenne was recently transferred in from our local animal control where she was surrendered when her owners could no longer care for her. Cayenne can be a little reserved around new people but we believe that is because she is not sure why she is in a shelter environment. She appears to have been well cared for in her past. Potty training and crate training unknown. Cayenne would love to get back into a home environment.

UPDATE: Cayenne is a beautiful 3-year-old, 66-pound, female pit bull mix who has a stunning reddish coat and infectious smile. Cayenne entered the shelter system on December 11th when she was surrendered to Tazewell County Animal Control because her family could no longer care for her, but Cayenne appears to have been well cared for and is healthy. She was later transferred to TAPS on December 21st. 

Cayenne is lively in the car, will jump from seat to seat and does not like to sit still. But she finally settled down when she found a human to sit next to. 

In my home, Cayenne was an absolute dream and if you are looking for a dog that is "chill", then Cayenne would be perfect for your home. She was not interested in toys (ropes, bones, balls, stuffed toys, etc.) and I do not know if it is because she is not interested, or if she never played with them in her past. However, Cayenne clearly has a true passion for food and was not picky about the type of kibble I fed her and loved all the different types of treats that I gave to her. 

Cayenne does not appear to know her basic commands of "sit", "stay", etc., but outside of a few attempts at counter-surfing, she is an incredibly quiet, calm girl who merely wanted to keep to herself. She did not try to get on my furniture and appeared to understand the phrase "let's go potty". Although she did have one accident in my house, but I believe her accident was my fault because her signals to go outside are subtle; so potential adopters will need to work with her on this to learn her cues. 

Overall, I found Cayenne to be sweet, quiet, and friendly and would be a good fit for most families. It is unknown if Cayenne likes other dogs or cats, but was recently cat tested and she was not reactive.

animal.description: And The Winner Is.... the lucky families who give these adorable Hound and Shepherd mixes a forever home. At around 6 to 7 months old, these superstars are ready to shower you with love and sweet puppy kisses. Since this litter of cutie pies came to Labs and More without mom or dad, we don't know what all they are mixed with or how big they will get, but we are guessing they will be on the large side or even extra large side when full grown. Elton is very smart, picking up several of his basic commands quickly. He is learning the leash and gets along great with kids. He is making great progress settling down in his crate. While it takes him a moment to warm up to new dogs, it isn't long before he starts play bowing and running around happily with them. Elton is looking for a family that understands the time, patience, and energy needed to raise a young pup. We require all puppy adopters to provide training that includes: house training, basic training, leash training, and socialization. Additionally, this cutie is going to need proper exercise, mental stimulation, and your attention and love to grow up to be the best companion. We do not allow our dogs or puppies to sleep or live outside; they must be incorporated into your family and be made a priority in your life. In return, you will have the most loving and loyal family member you could ask for. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting a puppy, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Looking for a fun-loving young dog who really knows how to enjoy life? That's our girl Harley, a 1 year-old who looks like she might be a mix of Pointer and Boxer but that's just a guess. Harley was found as a stray and when she wasn't claimed at the local county dog shelter, she made the trip to Canine Lifeline so she could have fun in a foster home while searching for her forever home. While we don't have any history on her pre-shelter life, we have found Harley to be a great dog! She has been friendly with all people and other dogs that she's met since coming to us. Harley loves to wrestle with other playful dogs so would enjoy having a fun-loving canine pal in her new home. She has excellent crate manners so should be able to pick up the house rules quickly in her new home. Harley hasn't had much experience on a leash yet so still needs some work on her leash manners. Using a harness with her as she gains more experience works best and makes walks more enjoyable. Harley showed her serious side for the camera but this girl usually has a big smile on her face and is ready for lots of fun adventures in her new home. Harley weighs about 34 pounds and her adoption fee is $350. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Harley. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Harley and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

This big sweet, lovable boy is Dexter, a 3 year-old who looks like a mix of St. Bernard and American Bulldog. Dexter found himself homeless after his family could no longer care for him. We were told that he was adopted by that family as a puppy and lived indoors for 8 months until they had a baby. At that time, Dexter was relegated to living outside. Fortunately, they finally realized (after 2 years outdoors) that this was not a good life for Dexter so surrendered him to the local shelter so he could find a warm, cozy indoor home and loving family. Dexter has been a wonderful boy since arriving here with us to work on finding the perfect new home. He acts like a big overgrown puppy and is very playful. He loves playing tug with toys but can be a little rough and mouthy when playing so wouldn't be a good match for children. Dexter will sit nicely for a treat and takes treats very gently for a big guy. He also walks quite nicely on a leash for a large dog, has excellent crate manners, and should be able to master the housetraining rules quickly in his new home with some positive direction on the part of his new family. Dexter gets along well with other dogs so might enjoy having a canine buddy in his new home too. He had a much needed bath when he arrived here and enjoyed all the attention that came with it. Dexter looks forward to living the rest of his life as a treasured family member and we can't wait to see him get that chance. Dexter weighs about 75 pounds and his adoption fee is $325. He's neutered, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Dexter. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Dexter and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
**AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION approximately 3-1-21 following heartworm treatment**

Big Bertha's story is one of deep sadness, you can see right into her broken soul through her eyes. Bertha had spent her whole life as a beloved pet, but her owner developed dementia and no longer recognized her own dog. She continued to call animal control to come pick up this stray dog, not realizing this was her precious companion. It became clear that Bertha was losing the home & master she so dearly loved, and was taken away to the rural pound where she slept on a cold concrete floor. Her heart & world shattered. She so longed to go home, but it was not meant to be. We aren't even sure what her name is. We can only work to restore the light in her eyes and the broken spirit behind them. We are committed to giving her everything she needs body & spirit. Will you please help Big Bertha in her journey to finding the happiness she once had by giving her a patient love & committed forever home? 

Big Bertha is a female Hound/Terrier/mixed breed, weighs 65 lbs and was born approximately 12-25-15. She is spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, given flea/tick preventative, dewormed. Bertha is undergoing life-saving treatment for heartworm disease. She will need to remain on heartworm preventative for life, as is recommended for ALL dogs, and retested in 6 months to ensure she is heartworm free. Adoption fee is $400 to help offset the many expenses we have for vetting costs. We rely strictly on adoption fees and donations to continue to save the lives of orphaned & abandoned pets; 100% goes towards their care. If interested in adopting one of our available dogs or puppies, please complete an online adoption application at https://dollyslegacyanimalrescue.org/adopt/ You will be contacted by our adoption coordinator via email after your application has been reviewed & approved to schedule an appointment.

animal.description:
Bane is a 4 year old Great Pyrenees in search of a new home through no fault of his.  He spent his life with a family as an inside pet until October 2020, when his family had to move in with relatives and he was unable to go with them,  due to space limitations.  They thought they found him a great home, where he would live a house pet, like he did with them.  Instead, he was kept outside, where he was shot at by neighbors, and supposedly did not like the person's teenage son.  He was then surrendered to an animal shelter, 6 weeks after they got him. Bane is heartbroken.   His name means Glorious Defender in Slavic.  He was recently diagnosed  with Lyme disease, and will be undergoing an antibiotic treatment.  His original owner said he was fine with their young children, who were born after they got him, other dogs, and guests in their home.  Bane does not do well with cats. We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Bane will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

animal.description:
One year old Ewing is our miracle pup. He was hit by a car and left for dead on October 23, 2020. A good samaritan (whom Ewing is named for) stopped to help and we rushed him to our vet. After seeing multiple other specialists, Ewing’s diagnosis is spinal cord damage. He does have some feeling in his right rear leg and has relearned how to walk. Ewing prefers to get around himself versus using a wheelchair. He’s even taught himself to do stairs; this boy is determined! Ewing is incontinent and wears diapers. We have him on a food that gives him nice solid bowel movements and together with the right style of diapers, makes it very manageable. Ewing is in a foster home with dogs and had even attended doggie daycare. He had learned the joy of playing with toys and does well with kids. Ewing has a very loving personality and you can tell he is grateful for this second chance! To adopt Ewing, apply at ITVrescue.org.

All of our animals are examined by a veterinarian, given age-appropriate vaccinations, dewormed, microchipped, spayed or neutered, heartworm tested and treated if necessary.

Please realize that many of our animals are kept in foster homes. Please complete an adoption application at http://itvrescue.org/adoption-application/ in order to meet with one of our animals. There is no obligation in completing the application, but it helps us find an animal that is most appropriate for your family.  The ITV Rescue Center is open Tuesdays 12-5; Wednesdays 12-7; Thursdays 12-5; Fridays 12-5 and Saturdays 10-5.  The Rescue Center is located at 1417 N. Stockwell Road.  You are welcome to come to our rescue center during open hours to see all of our great adoptable animals. Thank you for your interest in our animals!

NOTE: Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
Foster, foster to adopt, or forever home needed!

Remy is a female pit bull terrier mix, 4 years old and approximately 50 lbs. She is very high energy and loves attention, so she needs a family who can provide her with a large fenced area to run in, lots of mental stimulation, and plenty of love. She is very affectionate and enjoys spending time with people and playing with other dogs. She is excitable and doesn't know her size or strength so she is seeking a home without small dogs or young children. Other dogs in the home should be of a similar play style. Remy's rambunctious energy will be too much for an older or less playful dog.

Remy is potty trained and knows basic commands, but is easily overstimulated so needs some additional training to help her slow down and listen when she is excited. She also needs a little extra time outside, as her adventurous and curious nature sometimes distracts her from doing her business. She loves chew toys and ropes, which she will need plenty of so she doesn't get bored and resort to chewing her bedding.

Remy will be an incredible companion for an active family! If you are interested in fostering or adopting Remy, please submit the corresponding application at k9orphans.org to set up a meet and greet.

animal.description:
Logan is 5 years old, 70 lbs. He is super sweet but very strong. He is not good with other dogs

Meet Logan.  He is a very sweet people dog, but needs to be an only pet.

Logan has had quite a journey and is looking for his happily ever after.  Back in February of 2020, he wandered up on a good Samaritan’s porch looking for help.  He was emaciated and had healing wounds on his tale and legs that the vet thought were indicative of falling from a vehicle on asphalt. 

Logan quickly went to a foster where he got the care and rehabilitation he needed for several months.  We quickly learned what a love bug he is and how much he loves people.  He is a big cuddle bug at about 70 pounds, he’s goofy and doesn’t know his size.  He’s estimated to be 4-5 years old.

He loves hikes but he loves being a coach potato just as well.  He’s enjoyed trips to the mountains and sailing on the lake.  He is crate trained, house trained and knows basic commands. 

As noted, he needs to be an only pet.  He does not know how to interact with other dogs, and gets overly excited, which can lead to problems with another.  When on walks, if he sees another dog, he becomes fixated and barks excitedly.  While in foster care, we worked with a trainer to help with this.  It was working well, but training needs to be consistent.

In October, Logan thought he found his forever home.  However, his training was not continued in his new environment and the progress he had made slipped away and his new owner wanted a dog that could run and play with other dogs.  So Logan is being returned and needs another chance with someone who wants an only pet and is interested in continuing the simple training methods we’ve learned.

While Logan is best without other animals (cats or dogs), he is good with pretty much all people.  He’s great with kids.  However due to his size and strength, he’s probably best with children 10 and up.

This boy has a log of love to give.
animal.name: Logan

This precious, loving boy is blind and deaf. He suffers from glaucoma and will likely need to have both eyes removed in order to feel better. Dental work may be needed too, as this has been neglected for some time.

The good news is that Bobby is a happy little guy, adored by his foster mom and dad! He gets along well with their sweet, gentle dog and cat. He likes to go for walks and car rides. He loves to get cozy and warm and take his naps with his little stuffed toys, his people, and his fur siblings nearby.

Bobby would love a home where his people are home much of the time. Since he cannot see or hear, he does tend to bump into things until he gets to know his space well. Some basic precautions may need to be taken in his adoptive home in order to keep him safe. He would also benefit from a securely fenced yard that he can safely explore.

We are committed to getting Bobby the medical care he needs and finding him the perfect furever home! Could it be with you?

animal.description:
PLEASE READ: Mia is an intelligent and high drive pup looking for her forever home. She is easily excitable but is usually able to be redirected as she is food motivated and loves toys. She needs a home that has the patience to work with her quirks. She would do best in an adult-only home or a home with older children due to her intense herding nature. She loves to learn new things and would love a home that will continue to teach her. She loves to play with dog friends big and small. She loves to chase cats so no kitty friends please. If you are interested in meeting Mia please fill out an application and her foster mom will be in touch.

We do not have a facility for you to visit.

WE PROCESS APPLICANTS AND SET APPOINTMENTS BASED ON THE ORDER APPLICATIONS ARE RECEIVED

, so while you are welcome to email
ccrcdogs@ccrcdogs.com
with specific questions, you will want to complete the

ONLINE APPLICATION

ASAP

,

which can be found at www.ccrcdogs.com,

to secure your position in line for one of our dogs. You can also find

a description of our process on that same page. Puppies will not be available to be seen until their 10 day quarantine has passed. Our adoption fee is $200 for adults and $275 for puppies, which covers the cost of the spay/neuter, age appropriate shots and tests, medications to bring the dog to full health, and a free visit with one of our approved vets after adoption. The majority of dogs at CCRC are obtained from animal control centers, so there is often very little known about their history or even current habits. You can always expect to do some training, regardless of whether you adopt a dog or a puppy, including crate training, house training, and basic manners. CCRC provides a variety of materials and resources to assist you with this, as well as telephone support.

animal.description:
Fendi is a neutered male Hound/Rottweiler mix. He is about 4 and a half years old. He weighs about 75-80lbs. Fendi was surrendered to the Oakville and Milton Humane Society as his family could not care for him anymore. He is a high energy dog who requires lots of exercise.

This beautiful boy experiences some stress in his day to day life and is suspicious of new people, especially men. He responds well to treats and praise. Fendi is required to go to professional dog training classes. He is reactive towards other dogs and has not been able to make any dog friends while at the shelter. He also exhibits some signs of mild guarding of food and high valued items such as toys. He should not live with any other pets including, dogs, cats, or small animals. 

Once Fendi is more comfortable with someone, his sweet, playful side comes out. One of his favourite games to play is tug. However, he is still learning how to play appropriately without getting too worked up and resorting to unwanted behaviours such as mouthing and jumping up. Fendi does want to learn, and is a smart boy, but gets easily frustrated and overstimulated. If you are in his circle, he'll show you just how friendly and affectionate he can be. He will seek out attention and roll over for belly rubs and pets.

Fendi's home should have experience owning and working with large breed dogs. They should be active and excited to spend lots of time each day to exercising Fendi and working on his behaviours and training. A single-dwelling home with a fenced yard would be best (no apartments or condos). He must be adopted by an adult-only household (18+) without any other pets. He is not recommended for first time dog owners or people who want to exercise their pet at a dog park.

If you have the kind of home Fendi is looking for, and are interested in adopting a new best friend, please submit a Dog Adoption Application to the Adoptions department.

https://omhs.ca/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/OMHS-AdoptionApplication-Dog.pdf

You may submit your completed adoption application by placing it in our drop dox to the left of the shelter doors, by emailing it to adoptions@omhs.ca, or by faxing it to 905-845-1973. The adoption application must be submitted for a particular animal.

 Primary Color: Tan Secondary Color: White Weight: 35.2kg Age: 4yrs 4mths 2wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
COURTESY POST (NJ) - Ellie is a senior love bug that has been in boarding for a whole year due to her family losing their home during COVID and then not being able to bring her to the new housing. They cannot afford to pay for boarding much longer so we are helping her family find her a new home.

Ellie is an 11-year-old 55-pound terrier mix in good health. Her owners tell us she is a happy pup that does not act her age. She's great with all adults and she absolutely LOVES people. She wants to be around them and loves to just cuddle. She really enjoys lounging around and being able to look out the window or sunbathe. She usually gets nighttime zoomies but other than that, is mellow and lounges around the house. She likes to be tucked in under a blanket and be kept warm. She has select toys (tough toys that she cannot ingest) that she loves to play with.

Her perfect home would be a low-key place without a lot of foot traffic with older kids or adults only. No other pets in the home would be ideal but she may do OK with a submissive dog with owners with breed experience. She has been through so much and just needs a stress-free place where she doesn't need to adjust to a lot. She needs a home where her family understands she will need to settle into her new life and home and give her the time to do so.

Ellie is up to date on vaccines and spayed. Her adoption fee is $250. Please note this is not a LOVEPAWS dog so this will be a private adoption between the owner and applicant with the help of LOVEPAWS. Please considering making this sweet senior girl a member of your family and help her get out of boarding.

animal.description:
Ara s a two year old female Great Pyrenees surrendered to a kill shelter because her owner wos moving.  She loves cats and tolerates most other dogs.    The name Ara is a girl's name of Arabic, Armenian origin meaning "king".
Although it originated as a boys' name, in the contemporary US, it's now much more commonly used for girls. It's also used as a nickname for Arabella. A home with  male dog would be  best for her.  She would do fine in a household as the only pet too.  We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Ara will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

animal.description:
Johnny and Moira are a bonded pair who need to stay together. They have likely been together for their entire lives and have a loving dynamic that is a joy to see. Please note the individual details for each of them, as well as the information that applies to both.

Johnny Details
Just like his namesake, Johnny Rose, SWESR’s Johnny believes that “People Love Pizzazz.” He loves to play rowdy and is mischievous. Snow and water make Johnny’s “pizzazz” really come out. Playing in them, he is absolutely joyful. Another of Johnny’s joys is a boisterous romp with his bonded buddy Moira. After a fun-filled frolic with her, he is happy to lounge in the house and chew on a nylabone. He is affectionate with humans and loves a good massage.

Like the youngster that he is, Johnny puts everything in his mouth--from the dog bed, to shoes, to toys. Johnny may be a Large Munsterlander, but the DNA test isn’t back yet. Stay tuned for an update on that. No matter his breed, Johnny is pure doggy joy.

Moira Details
The beautiful Miss Moira has settled nicely into her foster home with her bonded buddy Johnny. She never has a grouchy moment, is affectionate, and loves to check everything out with her ever-busy nose. Like her famous namesake, Moira Rose, Miss Moira recently asked her foster mom “You do realize I’m a professional vocalist?” Her foster mom nodded in agreement as Miss Moira continued the conversation in her lovely professionally-trained dog voice. True to her breed, Moira is a Husky girl who loves to chat.

Moira and Johhny make a lovely bonded pair, with Moira being more dominant and Johhny not concerned about being the submissive one. Moira enjoys the snow and the doggie pool, running and wrestling with Johhny, but then settles nice indoors. 

Johnny and Moira
In their previous lives, Johnny and Moira were not shown the way to have proper house manners. Both are smart, treat-motivated and have already started clicker training. With gentle, consistent training, Johnny and Moira are learning the way to be great companions.

Because both of these dogs are big and active, they are not appropriate for a home with young children or frail adults. They are not cat safe, so a home without a cat is a must. Johnny and Moira will need a home with a secure fence of at least 6’ and room to stretch out and enjoy their boisterous style of play.

At about 2.5 years old, both these beautiful youngsters are house-trained, crate-trained, and fully vetted. They are currently in a foster home in Oklahoma and ready for adoption. For details and an application to adopt, please see http://www.swesr.org/Apply-to-Adopt.html
For an application to adopt or for more information about Southwest English Setter Rescue including our adoption requirements and transport availability, please go to http://www.swesr.org/. Please call us at 214-997-3885 if you have any questions.

You can learn about the adoption process and find a Word, PDF and ONLINE version of the questionnaire by visiting: http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/howtoadopt/.

Dog's Name: Sadie

Estimated Breed : Hound Mix

Approximate Age: 11 Months

Approximate Weight: approx. 51 lbs

Currently Living at: Boarding

Adoption Fee: $300

DOG'S DESCRIPTION

Sadie is a sweet sweet girl waiting for a loving forever home. Sadie is very friendly with people and loves playing around with other dogs. Sadie is quite strong and she is not aware of how big she is so she would be better off with older kids.

Your new pet will require a refresher in house-training. K-9 Lifesavers strongly recommends all new adopters enroll their new pet into obedience training. This provides for an easier transition into a new home, ensures the dog remains well socialized, and helps form a bond between the dog and the new family.

Adoption fees cover basic vetting, spay/neuter surgery (for dogs over 6 months old), rabies, distemper/parvo vaccinations, treatment for worms, heartworm testing, monthly heartworm prevention and monthly flea/tick prevention (while the animal is in our care), and transport costs from high-kill shelter. Please note that on average, K-9 Lifesavers spend significantly more on each dog than their adoption fee. Adoption fee for HW positive dog also covers heartworm treatment at our partner vets.

Foster Program: Foster homes provide for the temporary care of a rescue until the dog is placed into a loving, forever home. For more information on becoming a foster parent, and our Foster Program, visit http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/foster/ or email our Foster Coordinator at foster@k-9lifesavers.org

Sponsor Me! Make a tax-deductible donation today by visiting us at http://www.k-9lifesavers.org/donate/ . Donations help us offset boarding costs and additional medical treatment for those dogs who need it. K-9 Lifesavers receives NO federal funding and survive with your generous support!

For more information on K-9 Lifesavers, or to view a complete listing of all our Adoptable Dogs, visit our website at www.k-9lifesavers.org.

Please "like" our
Facebook Page
for the most current events and new dogs.

Thank you for considering a rescue dog!

animal.description:
Loving, playful & affectionate, everyone meet our #Queen #WiggleButt Ms. #Nala. She's 4 years old, 55lbs, and an American Staffordshire Terrier mix. At the end of the day, Nala is honestly just the biggest lover that you'll ever meet. Nala craves human companionship, loves her daily walks, enjoys sunbathing in the backyard, lives for belly rubs, she's all about cuddles & movie nights & loves to give big kisses. She's 100% potty trained, 100% crate trained and does well on a leash.  Nala knows all of her basic commands and is very eager to please. The perfect family for Nala would be one that is active, loves the outdoors, an avid runner or someone who loves going on daily walks, and definitely a family that loves cuddles & puppy kisses.

When it comes to people, Nala loves everyone she meets! She loves & adores children and would make the perfect family pet. She'd do best in a home with kids over 10 years of age because at times she doesn't always understand her strength. Nala would thrive best as the only dog in her furever home, although she has made a few friends while in our care. Nala does not do well with female dogs,  but does well with submissive male dogs with a proper introduction. But once again, we would like her to be the only dog in her forever home. Nala absolutely adores the cat that is currently in her foster home- especially when it comes to cuddle time.

Adoption Requirements: No Exceptions
- Fenced in Yard Required
- Needs to be the ONLY DOG in her new home
- Nala would thrive best as the only dog in the home, but does do well with most submissive male dogs & does great with the male cat in her current foster home

Want To See More Pics:
https://www.petfinder.com/dog/nala-50060051/mi/ferndale/pro-pet-otic-foundation-mi1050/

Nala is currently up for adoption through Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue located in Metro Detroit. Her adoption fee is $150  & will include her distemper, rabies, bordetella, parvo, & lepto vaccines; deworming; microchip; heartworm test; fecal test & being fixed. Nala is currently on both flea & tick prevention and has had her ProHeart 6 Injection for heartworm prevention. 

***PLEASE READ THIS ENTIRE POST & FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS****

Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue; previously known as the PRO-PET-OTIC Foundation, is a 100% Foster-Based Rescue that is ran by all Volunteers. Which means that we are not a shelter & each animal is in an actual home with a foster family. We kindly ask that you put any questions within the email & our team of Volunteers will get back to you. With the overwhelming amount of emails please be patient with our 100% volunteer family and we will get back to you. The application MUST BE filled out, a Vet Check MUST BE completed by our team, as well as a phone interview before we do a 'Meet N Greet.'
 
How To Apply:
If you're interested in adopting one of our available dogs:
1. Email LendingaHelpingPaw313@gmail.com with the dogs name as the subject when you ask for the adoption application.
2. Once you have completed the application, please print it out, fill it out, scan it, & then email it back to LendingAHelpingPaw313@gmail.com. If you do not have a scanner, please take a picture with your phone and we kindly ask that you sent all attachments into one email.
3. Please make sure to call your vet to grant our organization permission to do a vet check on your current pet.
4. If you are interested in more than one dog, please list your top 3 choices on the completed application.
5. Please be honest & truthful on your application. We always do a vet Check. We always do a home visit. And we always have both the prospective families & dogs best interest at heart!

Thank you in advance for all of your love & support,
The Lending A Helping Paw Dog Rescue Family

animal.description:
MEET BUSTER!!

Recommended for serious and patient adopters. We aren't sure about Buster's past, but he is incredibly scared and anxious. Buster has been at the shelter since 8/3/20 when he was brought to the shelter after biting a bicyclist. It appears based on his fear, timid and scared demeanor he has gone through a lot in his young life so far. Because of how scared he is when he meets new people and the bite incident, Buster will probably do best in a quiet and calm home without children. Buster will need time to adjust to a new home and potentially a crate or some kind of safe space for him while he adjusts. Buster is getting used to yard time but still retreats quickly to his kennel. Buster is such a handsome boy and deserves love and a home to call his own. Do you have the patience and time to devote to Buster that he deserves? Come visit Buster today! The Behavior staff is recommending placement with an adopter or rescue/new hope partner that is able to provide behavior intervention/support for fearful and undersocialized dogs.

Underdog Rescue does not physically have this dog in its possession. He is currently located at Maricopa County Animal Care & Control, Animal ID Number A4450301.

To visit with this pup, please make an appointment here: https://mcaccappointments.as.me/adopt. NOTE: People who sign up for these appointments often no-show, and we have seen that you can generally show up and let them know you are there to meet this particular dog and the shelter will squeeze you in, except from 12-3PM or closer to the 6PM closing time. (Please know this is not a guarantee). If the dog is at risk, please ask for a supervisor to meet that particular dog.

*Please Note: This animal is courtesy posted for the Maricopa County Shelter; UNDERDOG RESCUE DOES NOT HAVE THIS DOG. MCACC is located at 2500 S. 27th Avenue, Phoenix. Different adoption fees/policy may apply. Please visit MCACC's website http://www.maricopa.gov/pets/locations.aspx for hours. You may also wish to call 602-506-7387 (PETS) and provide the animal's A# above to verify is still available.

If you have additional questions please email info@huskyrescueteam.orgDerp!? Did anybody say Derp!? Only a Husky owner understands that term truly! And you know that means our Blue is silly, wonderful and a whole lot of fun! Blue is a freckled 3 year old fella. He was a rescue transfer from another agency who knew we'd be better suited to find Blue the right home. They took Blue in after he was found dragging a chain and had been missing for five months! His "owner" decided they didn't want him back. Our initial assessment shows Blue is dog friendly but still plays like a puppy, can scale a fence like nobody's business and wants to be where the people are. Classic Sibe! Blue will require breed experience or someone who's done extensive research, will let us further educate them and won't leave Blue for long periods of time, even post pandemic. Blue also needs another playful canine companion and a 6ft privacy fence. Video: https://youtu.be/LGZsasoOivo If you understand the breed, you'll appreciate Blue.

Blue is being fostered in NC - his adoption area is NJ to NC. He is able to be transported.

www.huskyrescueteam.org~~Husky Education And Rescue Team is a foster based rescue. Our dogs are in our foster homes all up and down the east coast. We do not have a facility in which you can visit. We find this a huge benefit because we learn our dogs and are able to educate our adopters on what it's like to have them live in your home. Part of our process, once pre-approved, is to speak with the foster for the dog you're interested in. If you're still interested in adopting from our rescue the first step is to complete our adoption application online at www.huskyrescueteam.org/apply

animal.description:
Caesar is an 11 year old, 65 pound (but should be 55 lb) male lab mix that was taken to a vet clinic, along with the cat that he lived with to be euthanized because the owners were moving THE NEXT DAY to a retirement community! Luckily, the vet refused to do it and asked for them to be surrendered to her.

He is absolutely the sweetest old soul! He gets along well with cats and calmer dogs (loves the ladies). He is great on a leash and enjoys short walks and long naps. He loves listening to jazz music! He does have some anxiety due to the huge change in his life, but routine, time to adjust, and jazz music has helped a lot as he has settled in the foster home. He sleeps all night on his bed and doesnt make a sound. He loves being outside and laying in the sun. Caesars ideal home would be with someone who is home most of the day, so that he can lay at their feet and keep them company. He does bark when you first leave him in a room, but give him a few of his favorite treats and turn on some jazz music and he will calm right down knowing that you will eventually come back! Caesar is also in need of some weight loss, and short slow walks are his favorite type of exercise. If you are looking for that dog to get you out moving a little more, Caesar is the one for you!

animal.description:
We would like to introduce you to our loving hound mix here at Saving Grace, Gibson! Gibson is a super sweet, cuddly dog who loves nothing more than being with his humans and would love to find a home where he is your one and only. He is so loving and appreciative of all the attention you can give him.
He's got very soft fur and is a wonderful snuggler! T
his sweet boy is around 3 years old, so still a young man, but through those puppy years. He is a great size at around 56 pounds.

He likes to play (stuffed squeaky toys are his fave) and do puppy pose to let you know he is ready to play. He's good at chasing and bringing back balls and is very athletic. On the other hand, he's just as content to curl up in his bed (one with cuddly sides) and snooze.

He is a smart, curious boy and is just so happy to get a scratch behind the ear. Gibson is excellent in the house, knows to potty outside.

Gibson is very good on a leash and has worked on learning "heel" and "leave it" without much trouble
.

Gibson does have a strong prey drive so probably best in a house without cats-and watch out for bunnies, squirrels and rabbits on walks because he'd love to chase them! He walks well on leash and tolerates his crate, although he'd much prefer to be with his people.

With his beautiful coloring and sweet personality, he just will melt your heart the second you meet him. If you think Gibson sounds like your perfect match, get your application in today to come to see for yourself why we love him so much!

Please note we are working with limited staff/volunteers at this time. For full details of our current adoption appointment policy, please see https://savinggracenc.org/adoption-appointments-during-this-time/. Highlights:

We are working with a very limited staff/volunteer base

We do not have the people power to respond to emails/call about specific dogs

Our appointments are limited to 2 people at a time and for a maximum of 30 minutes.

Please arrive at your appointment ready to meet the dogs we have available. At this time, many dogs are in foster families or not yet posted on our website. Be flexible and ready to meet any number of wonderful dogs available onsite at the time of your appointment.

All puppies and dogs at Saving Grace are crate trained, have been spayed/neutered, are up to date on their vaccinations, are on heartworm preventative and have been microchipped. Their adoption fee is $375.00. Each has been carefully screened for disposition and temperament in order to provide your home with a safe companion that will enjoy life as your new family member.

Our Adoption Form can be completed online at our website at https://savinggracenc.org/how-to-adopt/ .

An Adoption Form is required before setting up an appointment to meet with a potential adoptee or a foster home.

Sending an Adoption Form does not commit you to an adoption, it simply provides us with background information on potential homes.

If you'd like to donate to help cover the cost of care for these wonderful dogs awaiting new homes, please visit the donate page on our website at https://savinggracenc.org/donate-now/ .

Saving Grace is a small, non-profit 501-C3 organization operated by volunteers only. Most of our animals come from rural animal control shelters where lack of space and resources limit their time and adoption possibilities. Thank you for choosing Saving Grace! We look forward to helping you find your new companion and family member.
